\id PRO Original Douay-Rheims Bible
\ide UTF-8
\h Proverbs
\mt1 The Book of Proverbs,
which the Hebrews call Misle. משלי
\c 1
\p
\v 1 The Parables of Salomon, the son of David, king of Israel.
\v 2 To know wisdom, and discipline: \f + \fr 1:2 \ft By these sententious similitudes the studious may better conceive and understand true wisdom, and the virtues belonging thereto.\f*
\v 3 to understand the words of prudence: and to receive instruction of doctrine, justice, and judgment, and equity:
\v 4 that subtility may be given to little ones, knowledge and understanding to the youngman. \f + \fr 1:4 \ft profound & solid wit.\f*
\v 5 the wise man hearing shall be wise: and he that understandeth shall possess governments. \f + \fr 1:5 \ft Not only young men and inexperienced, but also the wise may learn more wisdom by these parables.\f* \f + \fr 1:5 \ft shall be fit to govern.\f*
\v 6 He shall understand a parable, and interpretation, the words of the wise, and their dark sayings.
\v 7 The fear of our Lord is the beginning of wisdom. Fools despise wisdom and doctrine. \f + \fr 1:7 \ft Fear of our Lord, that is, reverence of his divine Majesty with desire duly to serve him, and never to offend him, is the first degree in ascending to perfect wisdom: which consisteth not only in the understanding but also in action.\f*
\v 8 My son, hear the discipline of thy father, and leave not the law of thy mother: \f + \fr 1:8 \ft The first precept is to learn of our elders.\f*
\v 9 that grace may be added to thy head, and a chain of gold to thy neck.
\v 10 My son, if sinners shall entice thee, condescend not to them. \f + \fr 1:10 \ft The second to resist evil suggestions.\f*
\v 11 If they shall say: Come with us, let us lie in wait for blood, let us hide snares against the innocent without cause:
\v 12 let us swallow him alive as hell, and whole as one descending into the lake.
\v 13 We shall find all precious substance, we shall fill our house with spoils.
\v 14 Cast in thy lot with us, let there be one purse of us all.
\v 15 My son, walk not with them, stay thy foot from their paths.
\v 16 For their feet run to evil, and make haste to shed blood.
\v 17 But a net is cast in vain before the eyes of them that have wings. \f + \fr 1:17 \ft The proper remedy against such allurements is to be watchful, and to fly from them.\f*
\v 18 Themselves also lie in wait against their own blood, & practise deceits against their own souls.
\v 19 So the paths of every covetous man, take violently the souls of the possessors.
\v 20 Wisdom preacheth abroad, she giveth her voice in the streets.
\v 21 In the head of multitudes she cryeth, in the doors of the gates of the city she uttereth her words, saying:
\v 22 O children how long do you love infancy, and fools covet those things, which are hurtful to themselves, and the unwise hate knowledge?
\v 23 Turn ye at my correption: behold I will utter my spirit to you, and will shew you my words.
\v 24 Because I called, and you refused: I stretched out my hand, and there was none that regarded.
\v 25 You have despised all my counsel, and have neglected my reprehensions.
\v 26 I also will laugh in your destruction, and will scorn, when that shall come to you, which you feared.
\v 27 When sudden calamity shall fall on you, and destruction as a tempest shall be at hand: when tribulation and distress shall come upon you:
\v 28 Then shall they invocate me, and I will not hear: in the morning shall they arise, and shall not find me:
\v 29 for that they have hated discipline, and not received the fear of our Lord,
\v 30 nor consented to my counsel, & detracted from all my correption.
\v 31 They shall eat therefore the fruits of their way, and shall be filled with their own counsels.
\v 32 The aversion of little ones shall kill them, and the prosperity of fools shall destroy them.
\v 33 But he that shall hear me, shall rest without terror, and shall enjoy aboundance, fear of evils being taken away.
\c 2
\p
\v 1 My son, if thou wilt receive my words, and wilt hide my commandments with thee, \f + \fr 2:1 \ft This frequent manner of proposing the way and means to wisdom, If thou wilt receive my words, &c. sheweth most evidently the power of man's free will.\f*
\v 2 that thine ear may hear wisdom: incline thine heart to know prudence.
\v 3 For if thou shalt call for wisdom, and incline thine heart to prudence:
\v 4 If thou shalt seek her as money, and as treasures shalt dig her up: \f + \fr 2:4 \ft Not every desire, or sleight seeking of wisdom sufficeth, but such laborious seeking is required, as a covetous man seeketh treasure which he knoweth to be hid in the ground.\f*
\v 5 then shalt thou understand the fear of our Lord, and shalt find the knowledge of God.
\v 6 Because our Lord giveth wisdom: and out of his mouth prudence and knowledge.
\v 7 He will keep the salvation of the righteous, & protect them that walk simply.
\v 8 Keeping the paths of justice, & guarding the ways of Saints.
\v 9 Then shalt thou understand justice, and judgment, and equity, and every good path.
\v 10 If wisdom shall enter into thy heart, and knowledge please thy soul: \x + \xo 2:10 \xt Sap. 3. v. 32. 10. v. 9.\x*
\v 11 counsel shall keep thee, and prudence shall preserve thee,
\v 12 that thou mayst be delivered from the evil way, and from the man that speaketh perverse things:
\v 13 who leave the right way, and walk by dark ways: \f + \fr 2:13 \ft Adescription of perverse sinners especially of heretics.\f*
\v 14 who are glad when they have done evil, and rejoice in most wicked things:
\v 15 whose ways are perverse, and their steps infamous.
\v 16 That thou mayst be delivered from the strange woman, and from the foreigner, which mollifieth her words,
\v 17 forsaketh the guide of her youth,
\v 18 and hath forgotten the covenant of her God. For her house is bowed down to death, and her paths to hell.
\v 19 All that go in unto her, shall not return neither shall they apprehend the paths of life.
\v 20 That thou mayst walk in a good way: and mayst keep the paths of the just.
\v 21 For they that are right, shall dwell in the earth, and the simple shall continue in it.
\v 22 But the impious shall be destroyed from the earth: and they that do unjustly shall be taken away from it.
\c 3
\p
\v 1 My son, forget not my law, and let thy heart keep my precepts. \f + \fr 3:1 \ft It availeth little to hear good instructions, except we keep them in memory.\f* \f + \fr 3:1 \ft not in books only but in the heart:\f*
\v 2 For they shall add to thee length of days, and years of life, and peace.
\v 3 Let not mercy and truth leave thee, put them about thy throat and write them in the tables of thy heart: \f + \fr 3:3 \ft and put them in execution.\f*
\v 4 and thou shalt find grace; and good discipline before God and men.
\v 5 Have confidence in our Lord with all thy heart and lean not upon thine own prudence. \f + \fr 3:5 \ft Know also that all thy strength is in God, in whom thou mayst securely trust, not in thine own prudence.\f*
\v 6 In all thy ways think on him, and he will direct thy steps.
\v 7 Be not wise in thine own conceit: fear God, and depart from evil:
\v 8 for it shall be health to thy navel, and watering of thy bones.
\v 9 Honour our Lord with thy substance, and give to him of the first of all thy fruits:
\v 10 and thy barns shall be replenished with fullness, and thy presses shall run-over with wine.
\v 11 My son, cast not away the discipline of our Lord: neither do thou faint when thou art chastised of him:
\v 12 for whom our Lord loveth he chastiseth: and as a father in the son he pleaseth himself. \f + \fr 3:12 \ft Chastisement and tribulation in those that endeavour to serve God, is a sign of his favour towards them; and therefore his other promises which seem to be temporal, are to be understood of the next life.\f*
\v 13 Blessed is the man that findeth wisdom, and floweth with prudence:
\v 14 better is the purchasing thereof than merchandise of silver, and her fruit than chief and the purest gold:
\v 15 she is more precious than all riches: and all things that are desired, are not able to be compared with her.
\v 16 Length of days in her right hand, & in her left hand riches and glory. \f + \fr 3:16 \ft God rewardeth as it were with both hands, promising eternal life,\f* \f + \fr 3:16 \ft and competent means in this life.\f*
\v 17 Her ways are beautiful ways, and all her paths peaceable.
\v 18 She is a tree of life to them that shall apprehend her: and he that shall hold her is blessed.
\v 19 Our Lord by wisdom foundeth the earth, established the heavens by prudence.
\v 20 By his wisdom the depths have broken forth, and the clouds wax thick with dew.
\v 21 My son, let not these things depart from thine eyes: keep the law & counsel:
\v 22 and there shall be life to thy soul, and grace to thy jaws. \f + \fr 3:22 \ft Merit for the words of thy mouth.\f*
\v 23 Then shalt thou walk confidently in thy way, and thy foot shall not stumble:
\v 24 if thou sleep, thou shalt not fear: thou shalt rest, and thy sleep shall be sweet.
\v 25 Dread not at sudden terror, and the power of the impious falling upon thee.
\v 26 For our Lord will be at thy side, and will keep thy foot that thou be not taken.
\v 27 Do not prohibit him to do good, that is able: if thou be able, thyself also do good.
\v 28 Say not to thy friend: go, and return; and tomorrow I will give to thee: whereas thou mayst give forthwith. \f + \fr 3:28 \ft Alms in season is double worth to that which is deferred long.\f*
\v 29 Practise not evil against thy friend, when he hath affiance in thee.
\v 30 Contend not against man without cause, whereas he hath done thee no evil.
\v 31 Do not envy an unjust man, nor imitate his ways:
\v 32 because every deluder is an abomination of our Lord, and his communication is with the simple.
\v 33 There is poverty from our Lord in the house of the impious: but the habitations of the just shall be blessed.
\v 34 He shall delude the deluders, and to the mild he will give grace.
\v 35 The wise shall possess glory: the exaltation of fools ignominy.
\c 4
\p
\v 1 Children hear ye the father's discipline, and attend that you may know prudence.
\v 2 I will give you a good gift, forsake not my law.
\v 3 For I also was the son of my father, tender and as the only-begotten in my mother's sight: \f + \fr 4:3 \ft As Salomon was instructed by his father King David, so he teacheth others the right order how to learn wisdom.\f*
\v 4 and he taught me, & said: Let thy heart receive my words, keep my precepts, and thou shalt live.
\v 5 Possess wisdom, possess prudence: forget not, neither decline from the words of my mouth.
\v 6 Leave her not, and she will keep thee: love her, and she will preserve thee.
\v 7 The beginning of wisdom, possess wisdom, and in all thy possession purchase prudence: \f + \fr 4:7 \ft The first part of wisdom is to desire it. For nothing hindereth from being just but that justice is not desired. S. Aug. in Psal. 118. v. 20.\f*
\v 8 take her quickly, and she will exalt thee: thou shalt be glorified of her, when thou shalt embrace her.
\v 9 She will give to thy head increase of graces, and with a noble crown she will protect thee.
\v 10 Hear my son, and receive my words, that years of life may be multiplied to thee.
\v 11 The way of wisdom I will shew to thee, I will lead thee by the paths of equity.
\v 12 Which when thou shalt have entered, thy steps shall not be straitened, and running thou shalt not have a stumbling block.
\v 13 Hold discipline, leave it not: keep it, because the same is thy life.
\v 14 Be not delighted in the paths of the impious, neither let the way of the evil please thee.
\v 15 Fly from it, neither pass thou by it: go aside, and forsake it.
\v 16 For they sleep not unless they have done ill: and they take no sleep unless they supplant.
\v 17 They eat the bread of impiety, and drink the wine of iniquity.
\v 18 But the path of the just, as shining light, proceedeth even to perfect day.
\v 19 The way of the impious is darksome: they know not where they fall.
\v 20 My son hear my words, and incline thine ear to my sayings.
\v 21 Let them not depart from thine eyes, keep them in the midst of thy heart.
\v 22 For they are life to those that find them, and health to all flesh.
\v 23 With all guard keep thy heart, because life proceedeth from it. \f + \fr 4:23 \ft As the heart is the principal part of the body, so the will is the chiefest power of the soul: from which good or evil proceedeth.\f*
\v 24 Remove from thee a froward mouth, and let detracting lips be far from thee.
\v 25 Let thine eyes see right things, & let thine eye-lids go before thy steps.
\v 26 Direct the path to thy feet, and all thy ways shall be established.
\v 27 Decline not to the right hand, nor to the left: turn away thy foot from evil. For our Lord knoweth the ways that are on the right hand: but those are perverse, which are on the left hand. But he will make thy courses right, and thy ways he will bring forward in peace.
\c 5
\p
\v 1 My son, attend to my wisdom, and to my prudence incline thine ear,
\v 2 that thou mayst keep cogitations, and thy lips preserve discipline. \f + \fr 5:2 \ft To avoid all impiety it is first of all necessary, not to think, speak, nor hear unlawful things.\f*
\v 3 Attend not to the deceit of a woman: for the lips of an harlot are as a honey comb distilling, and her throat neater than oil. \f + \fr 5:3 \ft By woman is generally understood concupiscence of what sin soever, as. ch. 1. v. 10. & ch. 3. v. 33. ch. 4. v. 14.\f*
\v 4 But her later ends are bitter as wormwood, and sharp as a two edged sword.
\v 5 Her feet go down into death, and her steps penetrate unto hell.
\v 6 They walk not by the path of life, her steps are wandering, and unsearchable.
\v 7 Now therefore my son hear me, and depart not from the words of my mouth.
\v 8 Make thy way far from her, and approach not to the doors of her house.
\v 9 Give not thy honour to strangers, and thy years to the cruel. \f + \fr 5:9 \ft The world the flesh and the devil are strangers,\f* \f + \fr 5:9 \ft and cruel enemies that render for reward eternal damnation.\f*
\v 10 Lest perhaps strangers be filled with thy strength, and thy labours be in another man's house,
\v 11 and thou mourn in the end, when thou shalt have spent thy flesh and thy body, and say:
\v 12 Why have I detested discipline, and my heart consented not to reprehensions,
\v 13 nor I heard the voice of them that taught me, and have not inclined mine ear to masters?
\v 14 I have almost been in all evil, in the midst of the Church and of the synagogue.
\v 15 Drink water of thine own cistern, and the streams of thy well:
\v 16 Let thy fountains be derived abroad, and in the streets divide thy waters, \f + \fr 5:16 \ft Good doctrine is to be imparted to men of sincere intention.\f*
\v 17 Have them alone, neither let strangers be partakers with thee. \f + \fr 5:17 \ft not to contemners and obstinate infidels.\f*
\v 18 Let thy vein be blessed, and rejoice with the woman of thy youth:
\v 19 a hind most dear, and a most grateful fawn: let her breasts inebriate thee at all time, in her love be thou delighted continually.
\v 20 Why art thou seduced my son of a strange woman, and art cherished in the bosom of another?
\v 21 Our Lord beholdeth the ways of man, and considereth all his steps.
\v 22 His own iniquities take the impious, and he is fast bound with the ropes of his sins.
\v 23 He shall die because he hath not had discipline, and in the multitude of his folly he shall be deceived.
\c 6
\p
\v 1 My son if thou shalt be surety for thy friend, and hast made fast thy hand to a stranger, \f + \fr 6:1 \ft The wiseman doth not absolutely dissuade from all manner of suretyship, but from rashly, or unadvisedly answering for others. And especially exhorteth to use all diligence in performing, or causing others to perform that which is promised or covenanted.\f*
\v 2 thou art entrapped with the words of thy mouth, & caught with thine own words.
\v 3 Do therefore my son that which I say, and deliver thyself, because thou art fallen into the hand of thy neighbour. Run diverse ways, make haste, raise thy friend.
\v 4 Give not sleep to thine eyes, neither let thine eye-lids slumber.
\v 5 Deliver thyself as a little doe from the hand, and as a bird from the hand of the fowler.
\v 6 Go to the emmot, o sluggard, and consider her ways, and learn wisdom.
\v 7 Who whereas she hath no guide, nor master, nor captain,
\v 8 prepareth meat for herself in the summer, and gathereth in the harvest for to eat.
\v 9 How long wilt thou sleep, o sluggard? When wilt thou rise out of thy sleep?
\v 10 Thou shalt sleep a little, a little shalt thou slumber, a little shalt thou join thy hands to sleep:
\v 11 and penury shall come to thee, as a wayfaring man, and poverty as a man armed. But if thou be not sluggish, thy harvest shall come as a fountain, and penury shall fly far from thee.
\v 12 Aman that is an Apostata, a man unprofitable, goeth with perverse mouth, \f + \fr 6:12 \ft Every one that sinneth wittingly and of malice, refusing to obey God, employeth his mouth, eyes, feet, hands, and all parts with a wicked heart and intention to pervert others: most proper to heretics, apostates from the faith.\f*
\v 13 winketh with the eyes, treadeth with the foot, speaketh with the finger,
\v 14 with wicked heart he deviseth evil, and at all time he soweth brawls.
\v 15 To him his destruction shall come forthwith, and he shall suddenly be destroyed, neither shall he have remedy any more.
\v 16 Six things there are which our Lord hateth, and the seventh his soul detesteth:
\v 17 Lofty eyes, a lying tongue, hands that shed innocent blood,
\v 18 a heart that deviseth most wicked devices, feet swift to run into evil,
\v 19 a deceitful witness that uttereth lies, and him that among brethren soweth discords. \f + \fr 6:19 \ft The former six are all damnable, but this seventh is most detestable, because it is opposite to the chief virtue charity, it breaketh unity, & is the proper sin of the devil.\f*
\v 20 My son keep the precepts of thy father, and leave not the law of thy mother.
\v 21 Bind them in thy heart continually, and put them about thy throat.
\v 22 When thou shalt walk, let them go with thee: when thou shalt sleep, let them keep thee, and awaking talk with them.
\v 23 Because the commandment is a lamp, and the law a light, and the way of life the increpation of discipline:
\v 24 that they may keep thee from the evil woman, and from the fair spoken tongue of the stranger.
\v 25 Let not thy heart covet her beauty, be not caught with her becks:
\v 26 for the price of an harlot is scarce worth one loaf: but a woman catcheth the precious soul of man.
\v 27 Can a man hide fire in his bosom, that his garments burn not? \f + \fr 6:27 \ft All occasions of sin, especially probable, are to be\f*
\v 28 Or walk upon hot coals, that his soles be not burnt?
\v 29 so he that goeth in unto his neighbour's wife, shall not be clean when he shall touch her.
\v 30 It is no great fault, when a man shall have stolen: for he stealeth to fill his hungry soul: \f + \fr 6:30 \ft Theft is also mortal sin against the seventh commandment, but not so great as adultery.\f*
\v 31 also being taken he shall restore sevenfold, and shall give up all the substance of his house.
\v 32 But he that is an adulterer, for penury of heart shall destroy his own soul:
\v 33 shame and ignominy he gathereth to himself, & his reproach shall not be blotted out.
\v 34 Because the zeal and fury of the husband will not spare in the day of revenge,
\v 35 neither will he yield to any man's prayers, neither will he take for redemption very many gifts.
\c 7
\p
\v 1 My son keep my words, and my precepts hide with thee. Son, \f + \fr 7:1 \ft Because tentations still occur in this life, and man is frail, good exhortations, and earnest admonitions must also be continually inculcated, as here the wiseman often repeateth and much urgeth the same good and necessary advices to embrace wisdom and to walk still in the way of virtue, especially to flee from vices, and dangers of sin.\f*
\v 2 keep my commandments, and thou shalt live: and my law as the apple of thine eye:
\v 3 bind it on thy fingers, write it in the tables of thy heart.
\v 4 Say to wisdom, thou art my sister: & call prudence thy friend,
\v 5 that she may keep thee from the strange woman, and from the foreigner which maketh her words sweet.
\v 6 For out of the window of my house I looked out through the lattice,
\v 7 and I see little ones, I behold a foolish youngman,
\v 8 which passeth through the streets by the corner, and goeth nigh the way of her house,
\v 9 in the dark the day being toward evening, in the darkness of the night, and dimness.
\v 10 And behold the woman meeteth him in harlot's attire, prepared to deceive souls: babbling and wandering,
\v 11 impatient of rest, nor able to consist in the house on her feet,
\v 12 now abroad, now in the streets, now lying in wait near the corners.
\v 13 And taking the youngman she kisseth him, and with malapert countenance speaketh fair, saying:
\v 14 I vowed victims for welfare, this day I have payed my vows.
\v 15 Therefore I am come forth to meet thee, desirous to see, and I have found thee.
\v 16 I have woven my bed with cords, I have adorned it with tapestry pictured out of Ægypt.
\v 17 I have sprinkled my bed with myrrh, aloes, and cinnamon.
\v 18 Come let us be inebriated with breasts, and let us enjoy desired embracings, till the day appear.
\v 19 For my husband is not at home, he is gone a very long journey.
\v 20 he carried with him a bag of money: in the day of the full moon he will return to his house.
\v 21 She entangled him with many words, and with flattery of lips drew him.
\v 22 Immediately he followeth her as an oxe led to be a victim, & as a lamb playing the wanton, and not knowing that he is drawn as a fool to bonds, \f + \fr 7:22 \ft Sinners after consent given to tentations are as inconsiderate of their own state, & of their peril and ruin, as an oxe when he is led to the shambles, or a bird allured with a bait, that flieth into the snare or net.\f*
\v 23 till the arrow pierce his liver: as if a bird should make haste to the snare, and knoweth not that his life is in danger.
\v 24 Now therefore my son, hear me, and attend to the words of my mouth.
\v 25 Let not thy mind be drawn away in her ways: neither be thou deceived with her paths.
\v 26 For she hath cast down many wounded, and all the most strong are slain by her.
\v 27 Her house the ways of hell, penetrating to the inner parts of the death.
\c 8
\p
\v 1 Doth not wisdom cry, and prudence give her voice?
\v 2 Standing in the high & lofty tops over the way, in the midst of the paths, \f + \fr 8:2 \ft True wisdom directing to good life & so to eternal salvation, is only found in the visible Church standing upon a mountain, not hid in corners or obscure places.\f*
\v 3 beside the gates of the city in the very doors she speaketh, saying:
\v 4 O men, to you I cry, and my voice is to the children of men.
\v 5 O little ones understand subtilty, and ye unwise mark.
\v 6 Hear ye, because I will speak of great things: and my lips shall be opened to preach right things.
\v 7 My throat shall meditate truth, and my lips shall detest the impious.
\v 8 All my words are just, there is no wicked, nor perverse thing in them.
\v 9 They are right to them that understand, and just to them that find knowledge.
\v 10 Receive ye discipline, & not money: choose doctrine rather than gold.
\v 11 For wisdom is better than all most precious riches: and whatsoever is to be desired cannot be compared to it.
\v 12 I wisdom dwell in counsel, and am present in learned cogitations. \f + \fr 8:12 \ft These singular praises pertain to the increated wisdom, God himself, from whom proceedeth wisdom given to men by the Holy Ghost. See Annot. ch. 1. v. 2.\f*
\v 13 The fear of our Lord hateth evil: arrogancy, and pride, and wicked way, and a double tongued mouth I do detest.
\v 14 Mine is counsel & equity, prudence is mine, strength is mine.
\v 15 By me kings do reign, and the makers of laws decree just things.
\v 16 By me Princes rule, and the mighty decree justice.
\v 17 I love them that love me: and they that watch toward me shall find me.
\v 18 With me are riches, and glory, glorious riches, and justice.
\v 19 For my fruit is better than gold and precious stone, and my blossoms than chosen silver.
\v 20 I walk in the ways of justice, in the midst of the paths of judgment,
\v 21 that I may enrich them that love me, and may replenish their treasures.
\v 22 Our Lord possessed me in the beginning of his ways, before he had made any thing from the beginning.
\v 23 From eternity I was ordained & of old before the earth was made.
\v 24 The depths were not as yet, and I was now conceived, neither had the fountains of waters as yet gushed forth:
\v 25 the mountains with heavy hugeness stood not as yet: before the little hills I was brought forth:
\v 26 he had not yet made the earth, and the rivers, and the poles of the round world.
\v 27 When he prepared the heavens, I was present: when with a certain law and circuit he compassed the depths:
\v 28 When he established the firmament above, & poised the fountains of waters:
\v 29 when he compassed the sea with her limits, and set a law to the waters that they should not pass their bounds: when he hanged the foundations of the earth,
\v 30 I was with him framing all things: and was delighted every day, playing before him at all time,
\v 31 playing in the world: & my delights to be with the children of men. \f + \fr 8:31 \ft God much preferreth man before all other corporal creatures.\f*
\v 32 Now therefore children hear me: Blessed are they that keep my ways.
\v 33 Hear ye discipline, and be wise, and reject it not.
\v 34 Blessed is the man that heareth me, & that watcheth at my doors daily, & waiteth at the posts of my door.
\v 35 He that shall find me shall find life, and shall draw salvation of our Lord:
\v 36 but he that shall sin against me, shall hurt his own soul. All that hate me, love death.
\c 9
\p
\v 0 banquet of stolen water and hid bread.
\v 1 Wisdom hath built herself an house, she hath cut out seven pillars.
\v 2 She hath immolated her victims, mingled her wine, and set forth her table.
\v 3 She hath sent her hand-maids to call to the tower, and to the walls of the city:
\v 4 If any be a little one, let him come to me. And to the unwise she spake:
\v 5 Come, eat ye my bread, & drink the wine which I have mingled for you. \f + \fr 9:5 \ft S. Cyprian li. 2. ep. 3. citeth this whole passage of Christ's Sacrifice in the forms of bread and wine.\f*
\v 6 Leave infancy, and live, and walk by the ways of prudence.
\v 7 He that teacheth a scorner doth injury to himself; and he that rebuketh the impious, purchaseth a blot to himself.
\v 8 Rebuke not the scorner lest he hate thee. Rebuke a wise man, and he will love thee. \f + \fr 9:8 \ft Where is no hope of amendment prudence directeth us not to admonish, nor rebuke sinners, lest without any fruit we procure enmity, charity also requireth rather to expect\f* \f + \fr 9:8 \ft But when there is hope of good, every one is bound, especially superiors, to correct offenders. S. Aug. li. 1. c. 9. de civit. S. Basil. regulis fuse disput. 158.\f*
\v 9 Give occasion to a wise man, and wisdom shall be added to him. Teach the just, and he shall make haste to take it.
\v 10 The beginning of wisdom, the fear of our Lord: and the knowledge of the holy, prudence.
\v 11 For by me shall thy days be multiplied, and years of life shall be added to thee.
\v 12 If thou be wise, to thyself thou shalt be: and if a scorner, thou alone shalt bear the evil.
\v 13 Afoolish woman and clamorous, and full of allurements, and knowing nothing at all,
\v 14 sat in the doors of her house upon a seat in a high place of the city,
\v 15 to call them that pass by the way, and go on their journey:
\v 16 he that is a little one, let him turn to me. And to the fool she spake:
\v 17 Stolen waters are sweeter, and hidden bread more pleasant.
\v 18 And he was ignorant that giants are there, and her guests in the depths of hell.
\c 10
\p
\v 1 Awise son maketh the father glad: but a foolish son is the sorrow of his mother. \f + \fr 10:1 \ft Wisdom in general.\f*
\v 2 The treasures of impiety shall profit nothing: but justice shall deliver from death. \f + \fr 10:2 \ft Justice.\f*
\v 3 Our Lord will not afflict with famine the soul of the just, and the deceitful practices of the impious he will overthrow. \f + \fr 10:3 \ft Confidence in God.\f*
\v 4 The slothful hand hath wrought poverty: the hand of the strong getteth riches. Who so trusteth to lies feedeth the winds: and the self-same man followeth the flying birds. \f + \fr 10:4 \ft Industry.\f* \f + \fr 10:4 \ft Truth.\f*
\v 5 He that gathereth in the harvest, is a wise son: but he that snorteth in summer, is the son of confusion. \f + \fr 10:5 \ft Diligence.\f*
\v 6 The blessing of our Lord is upon the head of the just: but iniquity covereth the mouth of the impious. \f + \fr 10:6 \ft Equity.\f*
\v 7 The memory of the just is with praises: and the name of the impious shall rot. \f + \fr 10:7 \ft Good fame.\f*
\v 8 The wise of heart shall receive precepts: a fool is beaten with lips. \f + \fr 10:8 \ft Desire to learn.\f*
\v 9 He that walketh plainly, walketh confidently: but he that depraveth his ways, shall be manifest. \f + \fr 10:9 \ft Sincerity.\f*
\v 10 He that winketh with the eye, shall give sorrow: and the fool in lips shall be beaten. \f + \fr 10:10 \ft Unfeigned friendship.\f*
\v 11 Avein of life, the mouth of the just: and the mouth of the impious covereth iniquity. \f + \fr 10:11 \ft Wholesome talk.\f*
\v 12 Hatred raiseth brawls: and charity covereth all sins. \f + \fr 10:12 \ft Charity.\f*
\v 13 In the lips of the wise wisdom is found: and a rod on his back that lacketh wit. \f + \fr 10:13 \ft Prudent speech.\f*
\v 14 Wise men hide knowledge: but the mouth of the fool is next to confusion. \f + \fr 10:14 \ft Discretion in speaking.\f*
\v 15 The substance of a rich man, is a city of his strength: the fear of the poor their poverty. \f + \fr 10:15 \ft Just gain.\f*
\v 16 The work of the just unto life: but the fruit of the impious unto sin. \f + \fr 10:16 \ft Just intention.\f*
\v 17 The way of life, to him that keepeth discipline: but he that forsaketh reprehensions, erreth. \f + \fr 10:17 \ft Love to be corrected.\f*
\v 18 Lying lips hide hatred: he that uttereth contumely is unwise. \f + \fr 10:18 \ft Internal and external charity.\f*
\v 19 In much talk there shall not want sin: but he that moderateth his lips is most wise. \f + \fr 10:19 \ft Moderate speech.\f*
\v 20 The tongue of the just, is chosen silver: but the heart of the impious is nothing worth. \f + \fr 10:20 \ft Sincerity of heart.\f*
\v 21 The lips of the just teach very many: but they that are untaught, shall die in the penury of wit. \f + \fr 10:21 \ft Love of doctrine.\f*
\v 22 The blessing of our Lord maketh men rich: neither shall affliction be joined to them. \f + \fr 10:22 \ft Spiritual riches.\f*
\v 23 Afool worketh mischief as it were by laughter: but wisdom is prudence to a man. \f + \fr 10:23 \ft Sorrow for sin.\f*
\v 24 That which the impious feareth, shall come upon him: to the just their desire shall be given. \f + \fr 10:24 \ft Remorse of conscience.\f*
\v 25 As a tempest passing the impious shall not be: but the just as an everlasting foundation. \f + \fr 10:25 \ft Justice in general.\f*
\v 26 As vinegar to the teeth, and smoke to the eyes, so a sluggard to them that sent him. \f + \fr 10:26 \ft Diligence.\f*
\v 27 The fear of our Lord shall add days: and the years of the impious shall be shortened. \f + \fr 10:27 \ft Fear of God.\f*
\v 28 The expectation of the just is joy: but the hope of the impious shall perish. \f + \fr 10:28 \ft Piety.\f*
\v 29 The strength of the simple the way of our Lord: and fear is to them that work evil. \f + \fr 10:29 \ft Observation of God's law, fulfilling all justice.\f*
\v 30 The just for ever shall not be moved: but the impious shall not dwell on the earth.
\v 31 The mouth of the just shall bring forth wisdom: the tongue of the froward shall perish. \f + \fr 10:31 \ft Speaking and Meditating good things.\f*
\v 32 The lips of the just consider grateful things: and the mouth of the impious perverse things.
\c 11
\p
\v 1 Adeceitful balance, is abomination before God: and an equal weight is his will. \f + \fr 11:1 \ft Equity.\f*
\v 2 Where pride shall be, there shall be contumely also: but where humility, there also wisdom. \f + \fr 11:2 \ft Humility.\f*
\v 3 The simplicity of the just shall direct them: and the supplanting of the perverse shall waste them. \f + \fr 11:3 \ft Sincerity.\f*
\v 4 Riches shall not profit in the day of revenge: but justice shall deliver from death. \f + \fr 11:4 \ft Spiritual riches.\f*
\v 5 The justice of the simple shall direct his way: and the impious shall fall in his impiety. \f + \fr 11:5 \ft Piety.\f*
\v 6 The justice of the righteous shall deliver them: and the unjust shall be caught in their deceitful practices. \f + \fr 11:6 \ft Justice.\f*
\v 7 The impious man being dead, there shall be no hope any more: and the expectation of the careful shall perish. \f + \fr 11:7 \ft Care of the other life.\f*
\v 8 The just is delivered from distress: and the impious shall be given for him. \f + \fr 11:8 \ft Future joy.\f*
\v 9 The dissembler with his mouth deceiveth his friend: but the just shall be delivered by knowledge. \f + \fr 11:9 \ft Truth in words.\f*
\v 10 In the good things of the just the city shall rejoice; and in the destruction of the impious there shall be praise. \f + \fr 11:10 \ft Common good.\f*
\v 11 With the benediction of the just the city shall be exalted: and by the mouth of the impious it shall be subverted. \f + \fr 11:11 \ft Public joy.\f*
\v 12 He that despiseth his friend, lacketh heart: but the wise man will hold his peace. \f + \fr 11:12 \ft True friendship.\f*
\v 13 He that walketh fraudulently, revealeth secrets: but he that is faithful, concealeth the thing committed of his friend. \f + \fr 11:13 \ft Fidelity.\f*
\v 14 Where there is no governor, the people shall fall: but there is health where is much counsel. \f + \fr 11:14 \ft Good government.\f*
\v 15 He shall be afflicted with evil, that is surety for a stranger: but he that is ware of the snares, shall be secure. \f + \fr 11:15 \ft Prudence in suretyship.\f*
\v 16 Agracious woman shall find glory: and the strong shall have riches. \f + \fr 11:16 \ft Diligence.\f*
\v 17 A merciful man doth good to his kindred also. Benefacit animæ suæ vir misericors; qui autem crudelis est, etiam propinquos abjicit. \f + \fr 11:17 \ft Mercy.\f*
\v 18 The impious maketh an unstable work: but to him that soweth justice, is a faithful reward. \f + \fr 11:18 \ft Justice.\f*
\v 19 Clemency prepareth life: & the pursuing of evil things death. \f + \fr 11:19 \ft Clemency.\f*
\v 20 Aperverse heart is abominable to our Lord: and his will is in them that walk simply. \f + \fr 11:20 \ft Sincerity.\f*
\v 21 Hand in hand the evil man shall not be innocent: but the seed of the just shall be saved. \f + \fr 11:21 \ft Just dealing.\f*
\v 22 Aring of gold in a swine's snout, a fair woman & a fool. \f + \fr 11:22 \ft Internal virtue.\f*
\v 23 The desire of the just is all good: the expectation of the impious fury. \f + \fr 11:23 \ft Expectation of glory.\f*
\v 24 Some divide their own goods, and are made richer: others take violently not their own, and are always in poverty. \f + \fr 11:24 \ft Alms deeds.\f*
\v 25 The soul which blesseth, shall be made fat: and he that inebriateth himself shall also be inebriated. \f + \fr 11:25 \ft Benevolence.\f*
\v 26 He that hideth corn, shall be cursed among the peoples: but blessing upon the head of them that sell. \f + \fr 11:26 \ft Care of the poor.\f*
\v 27 Well riseth he early who seeketh good things: but he that is a searcher after evil things, shall be oppressed of them. \f + \fr 11:27 \ft Good desires.\f*
\v 28 He that trusteth in his riches shall fall: but the just shall spring as a green leaf. \f + \fr 11:28 \ft Trust in God's goodness.\f*
\v 29 He that troubleth his house, shall possess the winds: and he that is a fool shall serve the wise. \f + \fr 11:29 \ft Frugality.\f*
\v 30 The fruit of the just man a tree of life: and he that gaineth souls, is wise. \f + \fr 11:30 \ft Spiritual instruction.\f*
\v 31 If the just man receive in the earth, how much more the impious and sinner? \f + \fr 11:31 \ft Strait way of salvation.\f*
\c 12
\p
\v 1 He that loveth discipline, loveth knowledge: but he that hateth reprehensions is unwise. \f + \fr 12:1 \ft Love of discipline.\f*
\v 2 He that is good, shall draw grace from our Lord: but he that trusteth in his own cogitations, doth impiously. \f + \fr 12:2 \ft Progress in virtue.\f*
\v 3 Man shall not be strengthened by impiety: and the root of the just shall not be moved. \f + \fr 12:3 \ft Piety.\f*
\v 4 Adiligent woman is a crown to her husband: and putrefaction in his bones, she that doth things worthy of confusion. \f + \fr 12:4 \ft Diligent industry.\f*
\v 5 The cogitations of the just are judgments: & the counsels of the impious are fraudulent. \f + \fr 12:5 \ft Desire of justice.\f*
\v 6 The words of the impious lie in wait for blood: the mouth of the just shall deliver them. \f + \fr 12:6 \ft Sincerity in words.\f*
\v 7 Turn the impious, and they shall not be: but the house of the just shall be permanent. \f + \fr 12:7 \ft Justice.\f*
\v 8 Aman shall be known by his doctrine: but he that is vain and foolish, shall lie open to contempt. \f + \fr 12:8 \ft Sound doctrine.\f*
\v 9 Better is the poor and sufficient to himself, than he that is glorious and wanteth bread. \f + \fr 12:9 \ft Contentment of mind.\f*
\v 10 The just knoweth the lives of his beasts: but the bowels of the impious are cruel. \f + \fr 12:10 \ft Compassion.\f*
\v 11 He that tilleth his land, shall be filled with breads: but he that pursueth idleness is a very fool. He that is delighted in much quaffing of wine, leaveth contumely in his munitions. \f + \fr 12:11 \ft Diligent travail.\f* \f + \fr 12:11 \ft Temperance.\f*
\v 12 The desire of the impious is the muniment of the most wicked: but the root of the just shall prosper. \f + \fr 12:12 \ft * defence.\f* \f + \fr 12:12 \ft Just punishment of the wicked.\f*
\v 13 For the sins of the lips' ruin approacheth to the evil man: but the just escapeth out of distress. \f + \fr 12:13 \ft Guard of the tongue.\f*
\v 14 Of the fruit of his own mouth shall every man be replenished with good things, and according to the works of his hands it shall be repayed him. \f + \fr 12:14 \ft Godly instructions: and good deeds.\f*
\v 15 The way of a fool is right in his eyes: but he that is wise heareth counsels. \f + \fr 12:15 \ft Yielding to good counsel.\f*
\v 16 Afool by & by sheweth his anger: but he that dissembleth injuries is wise. \f + \fr 12:16 \ft Toleration of injuries.\f*
\v 17 He that speaketh that which he knoweth, is an utterer of justice: but he that lieth, is a fraudulent witness. \f + \fr 12:17 \ft True testimony.\f*
\v 18 There is that promiseth, and is pricked as it were with the sword of conscience: but the tongue of the wise is health. \f + \fr 12:18 \ft Advised promising.\f*
\v 19 The lip of truth shall be stable for ever: but he that is an hasty witness, frameth a tongue of lying. \f + \fr 12:19 \ft Considerate testimony.\f*
\v 20 Guile is in the heart of them that think evil things: but joy followeth them that give counsels of peace. \f + \fr 12:20 \ft Pacification.\f*
\v 21 It shall not make the just sorry what soever shall fall to him: but the impious shall be replenished with evil. \f + \fr 12:21 \ft Justice in general.\f*
\v 22 Lying lips are an abomination to our Lord: but they that do faithfully please him. \f + \fr 12:22 \ft Fidelity.\f*
\v 23 Acircumspect man concealeth knowledge: and the heart of the unwise provoketh folly. \f + \fr 12:23 \ft Prudent silence.\f*
\v 24 The hand of the strong shall rule, but that which is slothful, shall serve under tributes. \f + \fr 12:24 \ft Resistance of tentations.\f*
\v 25 Pensiveness in the heart of a man shall humble him, & with a good word he shall be made glad. \f + \fr 12:25 \ft Alacrity in good works.\f*
\v 26 He that neglecteth damage for a friend, is just: but the way of the impious shall deceive them. \f + \fr 12:26 \ft Friendship.\f*
\v 27 The fraudulent man shall not find gain: and the substance of a man shall be the price of gold. \f + \fr 12:27 \ft * a just man.\f* \f + \fr 12:27 \ft Honest industry.\f*
\v 28 In the path of justice, life: but the by-way leadeth to death. \f + \fr 12:28 \ft Good life.\f*
\c 13
\p
\v 1 Awise son is the doctrine of the father: but he that is a scorner, heareth not when he is rebuked. \f + \fr 13:1 \ft Filial fear.\f*
\v 2 Of the fruit of his own mouth man shall be filled with good things: but the soul of the prevaricators is wicked. \f + \fr 13:2 \ft Sound doctrine.\f*
\v 3 He that keepeth his mouth, keepeth his soul: but he that is unadvised to speak shall feel evils. \f + \fr 13:3 \ft Discretion in speech.\f*
\v 4 The sluggard will and will not: but the soul of them that work, shall be made fat. \f + \fr 13:4 \ft Constant endeavour.\f*
\v 5 The just shall detest a lying word: but the impious confoundeth, and shall be confounded. \f + \fr 13:5 \ft Truth in words and deeds.\f*
\v 6 Justice keepeth the way of the innocent: but impiety supplanteth the sinner. \f + \fr 13:6 \ft Justice.\f*
\v 7 There is one as it were with riches whereas he hath nothing: and there is as it were poor, whereas he is in much riches. \f + \fr 13:7 \ft True acknowledgment of temporal state.\f*
\v 8 The redemption of a man's life, his riches: but he that is poor, beareth not reprehension. \f + \fr 13:8 \ft Mediocrity of riches.\f*
\v 9 The light of the just maketh glad: but the candle of the impious shall be extinguished. \f + \fr 13:9 \ft Sincere conscience.\f*
\v 10 Among the proud there are always brawls: but they that do all things with counsel, are ruled by wisdom. \f + \fr 13:10 \ft Humility.\f*
\v 11 Substance hastened shall be diminished: but that which by little and little is gathered with the hand, shall be multiplied. \f + \fr 13:11 \ft Just gain.\f*
\v 12 Hope that is deferred afflicteth the soul: a tree of life the desire of ckoning. \f + \fr 13:12 \ft Speedy performance of promise.\f*
\v 13 Who so detracteth from any thing, he bindeth himself for the time to come: but he that feareth the precept, shall converse in peace. Guileful souls err in sins: the just are merciful & have pity. \f + \fr 13:13 \ft Good report.\f* \f + \fr 13:13 \ft Plain dealing.\f*
\v 14 The law of a wise man a fountain of life, that he may decline from the ruin of death. \f + \fr 13:14 \ft Good instruction.\f*
\v 15 Good doctrine shall give grace: in the way of contemners a whirlpool. \f + \fr 13:15 \ft True doctrine.\f*
\v 16 The subtle man doth all things with counsel: but he that is a fool openeth folly. \f + \fr 13:16 \ft Prudence.\f*
\v 17 The messenger of the impious shall fall into evil: but a faithful legate, is health. \f + \fr 13:17 \ft Faithful message.\f*
\v 18 Poverty, and ignominy, to him that forsaketh discipline: but he that yieldeth to him that rebuketh, shall be glorified. \f + \fr 13:18 \ft Desire to learn.\f*
\v 19 Desire if it be accomplished, delighteth the soul: fools detest them that fly evil things. \f + \fr 13:19 \ft Hate of sin.\f*
\v 20 He that walketh with the wise, shall be wise: a friend of fools shall be made like. \f + \fr 13:20 \ft Conversation with the good.\f*
\v 21 Evil pursueth sinners, and to the just good things shall be repayed. \f + \fr 13:21 \ft Justice.\f*
\v 22 The good man leaveth heirs, sons, and nephews: and the substance of the sinner is kept for the just. \f + \fr 13:22 \ft Succession.\f*
\v 23 Much meat in the tilled grounds of the fathers: and to others they are gathered without judgment. \f + \fr 13:23 \ft Frugality.\f*
\v 24 He that spareth the rod, hateth his child: but he that loveth him doth instantly nurture him. \f + \fr 13:24 \ft Chastisement.\f*
\v 25 The just eateth and filleth his soul: but the belly of the impious unsatiable. \f + \fr 13:25 \ft Contentment of state.\f*
\c 14
\p
\v 1 Awise woman buildeth her house: the unwise will with her hands destroy that also which is built. \f + \fr 14:1 \ft Frugal industry.\f*
\v 2 He that walketh in the right way, & feareth God, is despised of him, that goeth an infamous way. \f + \fr 14:2 \ft Fear of God.\f*
\v 3 In the mouth of a fool the rod of pride: but the lips of the wise keep them. \f + \fr 14:3 \ft Guard of the tongue.\f*
\v 4 Where oxen are not, the stall is empty: but where much corn is, there is the ox's strength manifest. \f + \fr 14:4 \ft Diligent labours.\f*
\v 5 Afaithful witness will not lie: but a deceitful witness uttereth a lie. \f + \fr 14:5 \ft Truth in all speech.\f*
\v 6 Ascorner seeketh wisdom and findeth it not: the doctrine of the prudent is easy. \f + \fr 14:6 \ft Seek wisdom.\f*
\v 7 Go against a foolish man, and he knoweth not the lips of prudence. \f + \fr 14:7 \ft Fellowship with the wise.\f*
\v 8 The wisdom of a discreet man is to understand his way: and the imprudence of fools erreth. \f + \fr 14:8 \ft Knowledge of ourselves.\f*
\v 9 Afool will laugh at sin, & among the just grace shall abide. \f + \fr 14:9 \ft Detestation of sin.\f*
\v 10 The heart that knoweth the bitterness of his soul, in his joy shall not the stranger be mingled. \f + \fr 14:10 \ft Internal comfort.\f*
\v 11 The house of the impious shall be rased: the tabernacles of the just shall spring. \f + \fr 14:11 \ft Contempt of this world.\f*
\v 12 There is a way, which seemeth to a man just: but the later ends thereof lead to death. \f + \fr 14:12 \ft The Catholic faith.\f*
\v 13 Laughter shall be mingled with sorrow, and mourning occupieth the later ends of joy. \f + \fr 14:13 \ft Spiritual joy.\f*
\v 14 Afool shall be replenished with his ways, and the good man shall be above him. \f + \fr 14:14 \ft Reward of works.\f*
\v 15 The innocent believeth every word: the discreet man considereth his steps. \f + \fr 14:15 \ft Believe not all reports.\f*
\v 16 Awise man feareth and declineth from evil: the fool leapeth over and is confident. \f + \fr 14:16 \ft Mature consideration.\f*
\v 17 The impatient man shall work folly: and the subtle man is odious. \f + \fr 14:17 \ft Patience.\f*
\v 18 The childish man shall possess folly, and the prudent shall expect knowledge. \f + \fr 14:18 \ft Desire of solid knowledge.\f* \x + \xo 14:18 \xt 1. Cor. 14. v. 20.\x*
\v 19 The evil shall lie down before the good, and the impious before the gates of the just. \f + \fr 14:19 \ft Piety shall be rewarded.\f*
\v 20 The poor shall be odious even to his neighbour: but the friends of the rich be many. \f + \fr 14:20 \ft Compassion of the poor.\f*
\v 21 He that despiseth his neighbour, sinneth: but he that hath pity on the poor, shall be blessed. \f + \fr 14:21 \ft Alms deeds.\f*
\v 22 They err that work evil: mercy and truth prepare good things. \f + \fr 14:22 \ft Mercy and verity.\f*
\v 23 In every work there shall be aboundance: but where many words are, there is oftentimes poverty. \f + \fr 14:23 \ft Good deeds with few words.\f*
\v 24 The crown of the wise, their riches: the folly of fools, imprudence. \f + \fr 14:24 \ft Right use of riches.\f*
\v 25 Afaithful witness delivereth souls: and the dissembler uttereth lies. \f + \fr 14:25 \ft Versipellis a turn-skin, or turn-coat.\f* \f + \fr 14:25 \ft True testimony. as v. 5.\f*
\v 26 In the fear of our Lord is confidence of strength, and to his children there shall be hope. \f + \fr 14:26 \ft Fear to offend\f*
\v 27 The fear of our Lord a fountain of life, that he may decline from the ruin of death. \f + \fr 14:27 \ft God preventeth punishment.\f*
\v 28 In the multitude of people the dignity of the king: and in fewness of people the ignominy of the Prince. \f + \fr 14:28 \ft Procure love and fidelity in subjects.\f*
\v 29 He that is patient, is governed with much wisdom: but he that is impatient, exalteth his folly. \f + \fr 14:29 \ft Patience.\f*
\v 30 Health of heart, the life of the flesh: envy, the putrefaction of the bones. \f + \fr 14:30 \ft Sincere intention.\f*
\v 31 He that doth calumniate the needy, upbraideth his maker: but he honoureth him, that hath pity on the poor. \f + \fr 14:31 \ft Compassion.\f*
\v 32 The impious shall be expelled in his malice: but the just hopeth in his death. \f + \fr 14:32 \ft Confidence in justice.\f*
\v 33 In the heart of the prudent resteth wisdom, & it shall instruct all the unlearned. \f + \fr 14:33 \ft Instruction of the ignorant.\f*
\v 34 Justice advanceth a nation: but sin maketh peoples miserable. \f + \fr 14:34 \ft Public justice.\f*
\v 35 Aservant that understandeth is acceptable to the king: he that is unprofitable shall sustain his anger. \f + \fr 14:35 \ft Industry in every man.\f*
\c 15
\p
\v 1 Asoft answer breaketh anger: and a hard word raiseth up fury. \f + \fr 15:1 \ft Meekness.\f*
\v 2 The tongue of the wise adorneth knowledge: the mouth of fools boileth forth folly. \f + \fr 15:2 \ft Discretion.\f*
\v 3 In every place the eyes of our Lord behold the good and the evil. \f + \fr 15:3 \ft God's omniscience.\f*
\v 4 Apeaceable tongue is a tree of life: but that which is immoderate, shall break the spirit. \f + \fr 15:4 \ft Calmness of speech.\f*
\v 5 Afool scorneth the discipline of his father: but he that regardeth reprehensions, shall become more prudent. In abundant justice there is greater force: but the cogitations of the impious shall be rooted out. \f + \fr 15:5 \ft Love to be corrected.\f*
\v 6 The house of the just is very much strength: and in the fruits of the impious is perturbation. \f + \fr 15:6 \ft Desire to fulfill all justice.\f*
\v 7 The lips of the wise shall sow knowledge: the heart of fools shall be unlike. \f + \fr 15:7 \ft Diligence in teaching others.\f*
\v 8 The victims of the impious are abominable to our Lord: the vows of the just are acceptable. \f + \fr 15:8 \ft Purity of heart.\f*
\v 9 The way of the impious is abomination to our Lord: he that followeth justice is beloved of him. \f + \fr 15:9 \ft Learn of good men.\f*
\v 10 The doctrine is evil of them that forsake the way of life: he that hateth reprehensions shall die.
\v 11 Hell and perdition are before our Lord: how much more the hearts of the children of men? \f + \fr 15:11 \ft All secrets known to God.\f*
\v 12 The pestilent man loveth not him that rebuketh him: nor goeth to the wise. \f + \fr 15:12 \ft Harken to good admonitions.\f*
\v 13 Aglad heart cheereth the face: in pensiveness of mind the spirit is cast down. \f + \fr 15:13 \ft Acheerful heart is desirous to learn.\f*
\v 14 The heart of the wise seeketh doctrine: and the mouth of fools is fed with unskillfulness.
\v 15 All the days of the poor are evil: a secure mind is as it were a continual feast. \f + \fr 15:15 \ft Aquiet mind.\f*
\v 16 Better is a little with the fear of our Lord, than great treasures and unsatiable. \f + \fr 15:16 \ft Contentment with sufficiency.\f*
\v 17 It is better to be called to herbs with charity: than to a fatted calf with hatred.
\v 18 An angry man stirreth brawls: he that is patient appeaseth those that are raised. \f + \fr 15:18 \ft Patience.\f*
\v 19 The way of the slothful is as an hedge of thorns: the way of the just is without offence. \f + \fr 15:19 \ft Diligence.\f*
\v 20 Awise son maketh the father joyful: and the foolish man despiseth his mother. \f + \fr 15:20 \ft Honour of parents.\f*
\v 21 Folly is joy to a fool: and the wise man directeth his steps. \f + \fr 15:21 \ft Discretion.\f*
\v 22 Cogitations are dissipated where there is no counsel: but where many counsellers are, they are confirmed. \f + \fr 15:22 \ft Desire to live well.\f*
\v 23 Aman rejoiceth in the sentence of his mouth: and a word in due time is best. \f + \fr 15:23 \ft Counsel in season.\f*
\v 24 The path of life above the learned, that he may decline from the lowest hell. \f + \fr 15:24 \ft To him that is well trained in good works, heaven gates are open.\f*
\v 25 Our Lord will destroy the house of the proud: and will make sure the borders of the widow.
\v 26 Evil cogitations are an abomination to our Lord: and pure speech most beautiful shall be confirmed of him. \f + \fr 15:26 \ft Honest thoughts and words.\f*
\v 27 He that pursueth avarice disturbeth his house: but he that hateth gifts shall live. By mercy and faith sins are purged: and by the fear of our Lord every one declineth from evil. \f + \fr 15:27 \ft Aliberal mind\f* \f + \fr 15:27 \ft Mercy and justice.\f*
\v 28 The mind of the just meditateth obedience: the mouth of the impious redoundeth with evils. \f + \fr 15:28 \ft Obedience.\f*
\v 29 Our Lord is far from the impious: and he will hear the prayers of the just. \f + \fr 15:29 \ft God assisteth the just.\f*
\v 30 The light of the eyes rejoiceth the soul: a good name fatteth the bones. \f + \fr 15:30 \ft Words of edification.\f*
\v 31 The ear that heareth the reprehensions of life, shall abide in the midst of the wise. \f + \fr 15:31 \ft Love of discipline,\f*
\v 32 He that rejecteth discipline, despiseth his soul: but he that yieldeth to reprehensions, is a possessor of the heart. \f + \fr 15:32 \ft and Admonition.\f*
\v 33 The fear of our Lord, the discipline of wisdom: and humility goeth before glory. \f + \fr 15:33 \ft Humility.\f*
\c 16
\p
\v 1 It pertaineth to man to prepare the heart: and to our Lord to govern the tongue. \f + \fr 16:1 \ft God's grace necessary in every good action.\f*
\v 2 All the ways of man are open to his eyes: our Lord is the weigher of spirits. \f + \fr 16:2 \ft Man's judgement is not secure.\f*
\v 3 Reveal thy works to our Lord: and thy cogitations shall be directed. \f + \fr 16:3 \ft Commend thine affairs to God.\f*
\v 4 Our Lord hath wrought all things for himself: the impious also to the evil day. \f + \fr 16:4 \ft God's providence.\f*
\v 5 Every arrogant man is an abomination to our Lord: although hand shall be to hand he is not innocent. The beginning of a good way, is to do justice: and it is more acceptable with God, than to immolate hosts. \f + \fr 16:5 \ft unpunished.\f* \f + \fr 16:5 \ft Punishment of sin.\f* \f + \fr 16:5 \ft Equity.\f*
\v 6 By mercy and truth iniquity is redeemed: and in the fear of our Lord evil is avoided. \f + \fr 16:6 \ft Mercy.\f*
\v 7 When the ways of man shall please our Lord, he will convert also his enemies to peace. \f + \fr 16:7 \ft Devotion.\f*
\v 8 Better is a little with justice, than much fruit with iniquity. \f + \fr 16:8 \ft Just gain.\f*
\v 9 The heart of man disposeth his way: but it pertaineth to our Lord to direct his progress. \f + \fr 16:9 \ft Necessity of God's grace.\f*
\v 10 Divination is in the lips of the king, his mouth shall not err in judgment. \f + \fr 16:10 \ft God assisteth superiors in governing their subjects.\f*
\v 11 Weight and balance are judgments of our Lord: and his work all the stones of the bag. \f + \fr 16:11 \ft Just balance do please God &\f*
\v 12 They are abominable to the king that do impiously: because the throne is established by justice. \f + \fr 16:12 \ft good kings.\f*
\v 13 The will of kings are just lips: he that speaketh right things shall be beloved. \f + \fr 16:13 \ft Righteousness.\f*
\v 14 The king's indignation, messengers of death: and the wise man will pacify it. \f + \fr 16:14 \ft Fear, and reverence of authority.\f*
\v 15 In the cheerfulness of the king's countenance is life: and his clemency is as the later shower.
\v 16 Possess wisdom, because it is better than gold: and get prudence, because it is more precious than silver. \f + \fr 16:16 \ft Love of wisdom.\f*
\v 17 The path of the just avoideth evils: the keeper of his soul keepeth his way. \f + \fr 16:17 \ft Justice in general.\f*
\v 18 Pride goeth before destruction, and before ruin the spirit shall be exalted. \f + \fr 16:18 \ft Humility.\f*
\v 19 It is better to be humbled with the meek, than to divide spoils with the proud. \f + \fr 16:19 \ft Meekness.\f*
\v 20 The learned in word shall find good things: and he that hopeth in our Lord, is blessed. \f + \fr 16:20 \ft Hope in God.\f*
\v 21 He that is wise in heart, shall be called prudent: and he that is sweet in speech shall find greater things. \f + \fr 16:21 \ft Mildness.\f*
\v 22 Afountain of life the learning of him that possesseth it: the doctrine of fools foolishness. \f + \fr 16:22 \ft Teaching others.\f*
\v 23 The heart of the wise shall instruct his mouth: and shall add grace to his lips. \f + \fr 16:23 \ft Sincere heart.\f*
\v 24 Well set words are a honey comb: sweetness of the soul the health of the bones. \f + \fr 16:24 \ft Sweetness in conversation.\f*
\v 25 There is a way that seemeth to a man right: and the later ends thereof lead to death. \f + \fr 16:25 \ft True faith & Religion.\f* \x + \xo 16:25 \xt Ch. 14. v. 2.\x*
\v 26 The soul of him that laboureth doth labour to himself, because his mouth hath compelled him. \f + \fr 16:26 \ft Proper industry.\f*
\v 27 The impious man diggeth evil, and in his lips fire burneth. \f + \fr 16:27 \ft Charity.\f*
\v 28 Aperverse man raiseth contentions: and one full of words separateth Princes. \f + \fr 16:28 \ft Common good.\f*
\v 29 An unjust man allureth his friend: and leadeth him by a way not good. \f + \fr 16:29 \ft True friendship.\f*
\v 30 He that with astonished eyes thinketh wicked things, biting his lips bringeth evil to pass. \f + \fr 16:30 \ft Sincere thoughts.\f*
\v 31 Acrown of dignity old age, which shall be found in the ways of justice. \f + \fr 16:31 \ft Holy old age.\f*
\v 32 Better is the patient than a strong man: and he that ruleth his mind, than the overthrower of cities. \f + \fr 16:32 \ft Patience.\f*
\v 33 Lots are cast into the bosom, but they are ordered of our Lord. \f + \fr 16:33 \ft God's providence.\f*
\c 17
\p
\v 1 Better is a dry morsel with joy, than a house full of victims with brawling. \f + \fr 17:1 \ft Peace.\f*
\v 2 Awise servant shall rule over foolish children, and divide inheritance among brethren. \f + \fr 17:2 \ft Wisdom in general.\f*
\v 3 As silver is tried by fire, and gold in the furnace: so our Lord proveth the hearts. \f + \fr 17:3 \ft Purification.\f*
\v 4 The evil man obeyeth an unjust tongue: and the deceitful obeyeth lying lips. \f + \fr 17:4 \ft Fellowship with the good.\f*
\v 5 He that despiseth the poor, upbraideth his maker: and he that rejoiceth at another man's ruin, shall not be unpunished. \f + \fr 17:5 \ft Commiseration.\f*
\v 6 The crown of old men the children's children: and the glory of children their fathers. \f + \fr 17:6 \ft Succession.\f*
\v 7 Eloquent words become not a fool, nor lying lips a Prince. \f + \fr 17:7 \ft Gravity in speech.\f*
\v 8 Amost grateful pearl, the expectation of him that expecteth: whither soever he turneth himself, he understandeth wisely. \f + \fr 17:8 \ft Desire of eternal life.\f*
\v 9 He that concealeth offence, seeketh friendships: he that in other word repeateth it, separateth the confederate. \f + \fr 17:9 \ft Remitting offences.\f*
\v 10 Reprehension doth more profit with a wiseman, than an hundred stripes with a fool. \f + \fr 17:10 \ft Discreet correction.\f*
\v 11 An evil man always seeketh brawls: but a cruel angel shall be sent against him. \f + \fr 17:11 \ft Concord.\f*
\v 12 It is better to meet a bear when her young are taken away, than a fool trusting to himself in his own folly. \f + \fr 17:12 \ft Gentleness.\f*
\v 13 He that rendereth evil things for good, evil shall not depart from his house. \f + \fr 17:13 \ft Gratitude.\f*
\v 14 He that letteth water go, is the head of brawls: & before he suffer contumely, he forsaketh judgment. \f + \fr 17:14 \ft Conservation of peace.\f*
\v 15 He that justifieth the impious, and he that condemneth the just, both are abominable before God. \f + \fr 17:15 \ft Just censure.\f*
\v 16 What doth it profit a fool to have riches, whereas he cannot buy wisdom? He that maketh his house high, seeketh ruin: and he that refuseth to learn, shall fall into evils. \f + \fr 17:16 \ft Spiritual riches.\f* \f + \fr 17:16 \ft Humility.\f*
\v 17 He loveth at all time that is a friend: and a brother is proved in distresses. \f + \fr 17:17 \ft Constancy.\f*
\v 18 Afoolish man will clap the hands, when he is surety for his friend. \f + \fr 17:18 \ft Carefulness in promising.\f*
\v 19 He that meditateth discords, loveth brawls: and he that exalteth the door, seeketh ruin. \f + \fr 17:19 \ft Concord.\f*
\v 20 He that is of a perverse heart, shall not find good: and he that turneth his tongue, shall fall into evil. \f + \fr 17:20 \ft Sincerity.\f*
\v 21 Afool is born to his own ignominy: but neither shall the father rejoice in a fool. \f + \fr 17:21 \ft Education of youth.\f*
\v 22 Ajoyful mind maketh a flourishing age, a sorrowful spirit dryeth up the bones. \f + \fr 17:22 \ft Alacrity of heart.\f*
\v 23 The impious receiveth gifts out of the bosom, that he may pervert the paths of judgment. \f + \fr 17:23 \ft Just judgement.\f*
\v 24 In the face of the prudent wisdom shineth: the eyes of fools are in the ends of the earth. \f + \fr 17:24 \ft Contempt of the world.\f*
\v 25 Afoolish son is the anger of the father: and the sorrow of the mother that bare him. \f + \fr 17:25 \ft Filial obedience.\f*
\v 26 It is not good to do hurt to the just: nor to strike the Prince, which judgeth right. \f + \fr 17:26 \ft Obedience to Magistrates.\f*
\v 27 He that moderateth his words, is learned and prudent: and the learned man is of a precious spirit. \f + \fr 17:27 \ft Discretion in speaking.\f*
\v 28 The fool also if he hold his peace, shall be reputed wise: and if he close his lips, a man of understanding. \f + \fr 17:28 \ft Moderate silence.\f*
\c 18
\p
\v 1 He seeketh occasions that will depart from a friend: he shall ever be subject to reproach. \f + \fr 18:1 \ft Constant amity.\f*
\v 2 Afool receiveth not the words of prudence: unless thou say those things which are in his heart. \f + \fr 18:2 \ft Harken to good counsel.\f*
\v 3 The impious when he shall come into the depth of sins, contemneth: but ignominy and reproach follow him. \f + \fr 18:3 \ft Speedy repentance.\f*
\v 4 Deep water words from the mouth of a man: and a stream overflowing the fountain of wisdom. \f + \fr 18:4 \ft a wiseman.\f* \f + \fr 18:4 \ft Wise discourse.\f*
\v 5 To accept the person of the impious in judgment is not good, that thou decline from the truth of judgment. \f + \fr 18:5 \ft Equity.\f*
\v 6 The lips of a fool mingle him with strife: and his mouth provoketh brawls. \f + \fr 18:6 \ft Study of peace.\f*
\v 7 The mouth of a fool is his destruction: and his lips are the ruin of his soul. \f + \fr 18:7 \ft Guard of the tongue.\f*
\v 8 The words of the double tongued, as it were simple: and the same come even to the inner part of the belly. Fear casteth down the slothful: and the souls of the effeminate shall be hungry. \f + \fr 18:8 \ft Avoid secret bate makers.\f* \f + \fr 18:8 \ft Fortitude.\f*
\v 9 He that is soft and dissolute in his work, is the brother of him that destroyeth his own works. \f + \fr 18:9 \ft Constant labour.\f*
\v 10 Amost strong tower, the name of our Lord: the just runneth to it, and shall be exalted. \f + \fr 18:10 \ft Confidence in God.\f*
\v 11 The substance of the rich man a city of his strength: and as a strong wall compassing him about. \f + \fr 18:11 \ft Spiritual riches.\f*
\v 12 Before he be broken, the heart of a man is exalted: and before he be glorified, it is humbled. \f + \fr 18:12 \ft Humility.\f*
\v 13 He that answereth before he hear, sheweth himself to be a fool, and worthy of confusion. \f + \fr 18:13 \ft Consideration in answering.\f*
\v 14 The spirit of a man upholdeth his imbecility: but a spirit that is easy to be angry who can sustain? \f + \fr 18:14 \ft Quietness of spirit.\f*
\v 15 Awise heart shall possess knowledge: and the ear of the wise seeketh doctrine. \f + \fr 18:15 \ft Desire to learn.\f*
\v 16 The gift of a man enlargeth his way, & maketh him room before Princes. \f + \fr 18:16 \ft Alms deeds.\f*
\v 17 The just is first accuser of himself: his friend cometh, and shall search him. \f + \fr 18:17 \ft Acknowledging of faults.\f*
\v 18 Lot suppresseth contradictions, and between the mighty also it determineth. \f + \fr 18:18 \ft Use of lot to make agreement.\f*
\v 19 Brother that is holpen of brother, is a strong city: and judgments are as the bars of cities. \f + \fr 18:19 \ft Fraternal concord.\f*
\v 20 Of the fruit of man's mouth his belly shall be filled: and the offsprings of his lips shall fill him. \f + \fr 18:20 \ft Godly instructions.\f*
\v 21 Death and life in the hand of the tongue: they that love it, shall eat the fruits thereof. \f + \fr 18:21 \ft Right use of the tongue.\f*
\v 22 He that hath found a good wife, hath found a good thing, and hath received a pleasure of our Lord. \f + \fr 18:22 \ft Awife's virtue is her best dowry.\f*
\v 23 The poor speaketh with supplications, and the rich will speak roughly. \f + \fr 18:23 \ft Meekness.\f*
\v 24 Aman amiable to society, shall be more friendly than a brother. \f + \fr 18:24 \ft Amity with affability.\f*
\c 19
\p
\v 1 Better is a poor man, that walketh in his simplicity, than a rich writhing his lips, and unwise. \f + \fr 19:1 \ft Honest poverty.\f*
\v 2 Where is no knowledge of the soul, is not good: and he that is hasty with his feet shall stumble. \f + \fr 19:2 \ft Knowledge of ourselves.\f*
\v 3 The folly of a man supplanteth his steps: and he boileth in his mind against God. \f + \fr 19:3 \ft Man's own will the cause of evil.\f*
\v 4 Riches add many friends: but from the poor they also which he had are separated. \f + \fr 19:4 \ft Spiritual riches secure.\f*
\v 5 Afalse witness shall not be unpunished: & he that speaketh lies, shall not escape. \f + \fr 19:5 \ft True testimony.\f*
\v 6 Many worship the person of the mighty, and are friends of him that giveth gifts. \f + \fr 19:6 \ft Liberality.\f*
\v 7 The brethren of the poor man hate him: moreover also his friends have departed far from him. \f + \fr 19:7 \ft Industrious travail.\f*
\v 8 He that pursueth words only, shall have nothing: but he that is possessor of the mind, loveth his soul, and the keeper of prudence shall find good things. \f + \fr 19:8 \ft Solid doctrine.\f*
\v 9 Afalse witness shall not be unpunished: and he that speaketh lies shall perish. \f + \fr 19:9 \ft True testimony.\f*
\v 10 Delicacies become not a fool: nor a servant to rule over Princes. \f + \fr 19:10 \ft Wise & fit magistrates.\f*
\v 11 The doctrine of man is known by patience: and his glory is to overpass unjust things. \f + \fr 19:11 \ft Patience in teachers.\f*
\v 12 As the roaring of a lion, so also the anger of a king: and as dew upon grass, so also his cheerfulness. \f + \fr 19:12 \ft Loyalty to Kings, and princes.\f*
\v 13 The sorrow of the father, a foolish son: and roofs continually dropping through, a woman full of brawling. \f + \fr 19:13 \ft Domestical peace.\f*
\v 14 House and riches are given of the parents: but of our Lord properly a prudent wife. \f + \fr 19:14 \ft Agood wife is God's gift.\f*
\v 15 Slothfulness bringeth drowsiness, and a dissolute soul shall be an hungered. \f + \fr 19:15 \ft Diligence.\f*
\v 16 He that keepeth the commandment, keepeth his soul: but he that neglecteth his way, shall die. \f + \fr 19:16 \ft Obedience.\f*
\v 17 He lendeth our Lord that hath mercy on the poor: and he will repay him the like. \f + \fr 19:17 \ft Alms deeds.\f*
\v 18 Nurture thy son, despair not: but to the killing of him set not thy soul. \f + \fr 19:18 \ft Moderate chastisement.\f*
\v 19 He that is impatient shall sustain damage: and when he shall take away violently, he shall add another thing. \f + \fr 19:19 \ft Patience.\f*
\v 20 Hear counsel, and receive discipline, that thou mayst be wise in thy later ends. \f + \fr 19:20 \ft Follow good counsel.\f*
\v 21 Many cogitations in the heart of a man: but the will of our Lord shall be permanent. \f + \fr 19:21 \ft Trust in God.\f*
\v 22 Aneedy man is merciful: and better is the poor than the lying man. \f + \fr 19:22 \ft Good will to help the poor.\f*
\v 23 The fear of our Lord unto life: and in fullness he shall abide, without the visitation most noisome: \f + \fr 19:23 \ft Fear of God.\f*
\v 24 The slothful hideth his hand under the arm-hole, neither doth he put it to his mouth. \f + \fr 19:24 \ft Diligent travail.\f*
\v 25 The pestilent man being whipped, the fool shall be wiser: but if thou rebuke a wiseman he will understand discipline. \f + \fr 19:25 \ft Just correction.\f*
\v 26 He that afflicteth his father, and flyeth from his mother, is ignominious and unhappy. \f + \fr 19:26 \ft Honour of parents.\f*
\v 27 Cease not, o son, to hear doctrine, neither be ignorant of the words of knowledge. \f + \fr 19:27 \ft Desire to learn.\f*
\v 28 An unjust witness scorneth judgment: and the mouth of the impious devoureth iniquity. \f + \fr 19:28 \ft True testimony.\f*
\v 29 Judgments are prepared for scorners: & hammers striking for the bodies of fools. \f + \fr 19:29 \ft Fear of eternal punishment.\f*
\c 20
\p
\v 1 Wine is a luxurious thing, & drunkenness tumultuous: whosoever is delighted therewith shall not be wise. \f + \fr 20:1 \ft Sobriety.\f*
\v 2 As the roaring of a lion, so also the terror of a king: he that provoketh him, sinneth also against his own soul. \f + \fr 20:2 \ft Obedience to Princes.\f*
\v 3 It is honour to a man that separateth himself from contentions: but all fools meddle with contumelies. \f + \fr 20:3 \ft Concord.\f*
\v 4 Because of cold the slothful would not plow: he shall beg therefore in the summer, and it shall not be given him. \f + \fr 20:4 \ft Industry.\f*
\v 5 As deep water, so counsel in the heart of a man: but a wise man shall draw it out. \f + \fr 20:5 \ft Profound counsel.\f*
\v 6 Many men are called merciful: but a faithful man who shall find? \f + \fr 20:6 \ft Fidelity.\f*
\v 7 The just that walketh in his simplicity, shall leave blessed children. \f + \fr 20:7 \ft Sincerity.\f*
\v 8 The king that sitteth in the throne of judgment, dissipateth all evil with his look. \f + \fr 20:8 \ft Execution of Justice.\f*
\v 9 Who can say: My heart is clean, I am pure from sin? \f + \fr 20:9 \ft Necessity of grace.\f*
\v 10 Weight and weight, measure and measure: both are abominable before God. \f + \fr 20:10 \ft Equity.\f*
\v 11 By his conversation a child is perceived, if his works be clean and right. \f + \fr 20:11 \ft Good towardliness.\f*
\v 12 The ear hearing, and the eye seeing, our Lord made both. \f + \fr 20:12 \ft Right use of senses.\f*
\v 13 Love not sleep, lest poverty oppress thee: open thine eyes and be filled with breads. \f + \fr 20:13 \ft Diligent travail.\f*
\v 14 It is naught, it is naught, saith every buyer: and when he is departed he will boast. \f + \fr 20:14 \ft Prudence.\f*
\v 15 There is gold, and multitude of pearls: but a precious vessel the lips of knowledge. \f + \fr 20:15 \ft Knowledge is a jewel.\f*
\v 16 Take his garment, that was the surety of a stranger, and for strangers take a pledge from him. \f + \fr 20:16 \ft Security in suretyship.\f*
\v 17 The bread of lying is sweet to a man: and afterward his mouth shall be filled with the gravel stone. \f + \fr 20:17 \ft Truth.\f*
\v 18 Cogitations are strengthened by counsels: and battles are to be handled by governments. \f + \fr 20:18 \ft Counsel in war.\f*
\v 19 Meddle not with him that revealeth mysteries, and walketh fraudulently, and dilateth his lips. \f + \fr 20:19 \ft Consult with the faithful.\f*
\v 20 He that curseth his father, and mother, his lamp shall be extinguished in the midst of darkness. \f + \fr 20:20 \ft Honour of parents.\f*
\v 21 The inheritance whereunto haste is made in the beginning, in the later end shall lack blessing. \f + \fr 20:21 \ft Lawful gain.\f*
\v 22 Say not, I will requite evil: expect our Lord, and he will deliver thee. \f + \fr 20:22 \ft Meekness.\f*
\v 23 Weight and weight are abomination with our Lord: a deceitful balance is not good. \f + \fr 20:23 \ft Equity.\f*
\v 24 The steps of man are directed of our Lord: but who of men can understand his own way? \f + \fr 20:24 \ft Trust in God's providence.\f*
\v 25 It is ruin to a man to devour saints, and afterward to retract the vows. \f + \fr 20:25 \ft Performance of vows.\f*
\v 26 Awise king dissipateth the impious, and bendeth over them a triumphant arch. \f + \fr 20:26 \ft Public justice.\f*
\v 27 The lamp of our Lord, the breath of a man, which searcheth all the secrets of the belly. \f + \fr 20:27 \ft Purity of mind.\f*
\v 28 Mercy & truth keep the king, and his throne is strengthened by clemency. \f + \fr 20:28 \ft Three kingly virtues.\f*
\v 29 The joy of youngmen their strength: and the dignity of oldmen a gray head. \f + \fr 20:29 \ft Prudence with fortitude.\f*
\v 30 The blueness of the wound shall wipe away evils: and stripes in the more secret place of the belly. \f + \fr 20:30 \ft Punishment of sins.\f*
\c 21
\p
\v 1 As divisions of waters, so the heart of the king is in the hand of our Lord: whither soever he will, he shall incline it. \f + \fr 21:1 \ft God's providence.\f*
\v 2 Every way of a man seemeth to himself right: but our Lord weigheth the hearts. \f + \fr 21:2 \ft ch. 14. v. 12. & 16. v. 2.\f*
\v 3 To do mercy and judgment, doth more please our Lord than victims. \f + \fr 21:3 \ft Mercy and judgement.\f*
\v 4 Exaltation of the eyes is the dilation of the heart: the lamp of the impious sin. \f + \fr 21:4 \ft Humility.\f*
\v 5 The cogitations of the strong are always in aboundance: but every sluggard is always in poverty. \f + \fr 21:5 \ft Fortitude.\f*
\v 6 He that gathereth treasures with a lying tongue is vain and witless, and shall stumble at the snares of death. \f + \fr 21:6 \ft Truth.\f*
\v 7 The robberies of the impious shall draw them down, because they would not do judgment. \f + \fr 21:7 \ft Equity.\f*
\v 8 The perverse way of a man is strange: but he that is clean, his work is right. \f + \fr 21:8 \ft Right in heart.\f*
\v 9 It is better to sit in a corner of the house top, than with a brawling woman, and in a common house. \f + \fr 21:9 \ft Domestical peace.\f*
\v 10 The soul of the impious desireth evil, he will not have pity on his neighbour. \f + \fr 21:10 \ft Commiseration.\f*
\v 11 The pestilent man being punished, the little one will be wiser: and if he follow the wiseman, he will take knowledge. \f + \fr 21:11 \ft Chastisement of sin.\f*
\v 12 The just deviseth concerning the house of the impious, that he may draw the impious from evil. \f + \fr 21:12 \ft Charity.\f*
\v 13 He that stoppeth his ear at the cry of the poor, himself also shall cry and shall not be heard. \f + \fr 21:13 \ft Alms deeds.\f*
\v 14 Agift hid quencheth angers: and a gift in the bosom the greatest indignation. \f + \fr 21:14 \ft Alms in secret.\f*
\v 15 It is a joy to the just to do judgment: and dread to them that work iniquity. \f + \fr 21:15 \ft Just punishment.\f*
\v 16 Aman, that shall err from the way of doctrine, shall abide in the assembly of giants. \f + \fr 21:16 \ft Observation of orders.\f*
\v 17 He that loveth good cheer, shall be in poverty: he that loveth wine, and fat things, shall not be rich. \f + \fr 21:17 \ft Temperance & parsimony.\f*
\v 18 The impious shall be given for the just: and the unjust for the righteous. \f + \fr 21:18 \ft Piety.\f*
\v 19 It is better to dwell in a desert land, than with a brawling and angry woman. \f + \fr 21:19 \ft Domestical peace.\f*
\v 20 Treasure to be desired, and oil in the habitation of the just: and the unwise man shall dissipate it. \f + \fr 21:20 \ft Frugality.\f*
\v 21 He that followeth justice and mercy, shall find life, justice, and glory. \f + \fr 21:21 \ft Justice and mercy.\f*
\v 22 The wise hath scaled the city of the strong, and hath destroyed the confidence thereof. \f + \fr 21:22 \ft Fortitude.\f*
\v 23 He that keepeth his mouth, and his tongue, keepeth his soul from distresses. \f + \fr 21:23 \ft Guard of the tongue.\f*
\v 24 The proud and arrogant is called unlearned, which in anger worketh pride. \f + \fr 21:24 \ft Modesty.\f*
\v 25 Desires kill the slothful: for his hands would not work any thing: \f + \fr 21:25 \ft Diligent travail.\f*
\v 26 all the day he longeth and desireth: but he that is just, will give, and will not cease. \f + \fr 21:26 \ft Liberality.\f*
\v 27 The hosts of the impious abominable, because they are offered of wickedness. \f + \fr 21:27 \ft Sincerity in religion.\f*
\v 28 Alying witness shall perish: an obedient man shall speak victory. \f + \fr 21:28 \ft True testimony, and sound doctrine.\f*
\v 29 The impious man malapertly hardeneth his countenance: but he that is righteous, correcteth his way. \f + \fr 21:29 \ft Amendment of faults.\f*
\v 30 There is no wisdom, there is no prudence, there is no counsel against our Lord. \f + \fr 21:30 \ft Conformity to God's will.\f*
\v 31 The horse is prepared to the day of battle: but our Lord giveth salvation. \f + \fr 21:31 \ft God's grace necessary.\f*
\c 22
\p
\v 1 Better is a good name, than much riches: above silver and gold, good grace. \f + \fr 22:1 \ft Honest fame.\f*
\v 2 The rich and poor have met one another: our Lord is the maker of both. \f + \fr 22:2 \ft Contentment without state.\f*
\v 3 The subtle saw evil, and hid himself: the innocent passed by, and was afflicted with damage. \f + \fr 22:3 \ft Prudence.\f*
\v 4 The end of modesty the fear of our Lord, riches and glory and life. \f + \fr 22:4 \ft Poverty of spirit.\f*
\v 5 Armour and swords in the way of the perverse: but the keeper of his own soul departeth far from them.
\v 6 It is a proverb: A youngman according to his way, when he is old will not depart from it. \f + \fr 22:6 \ft Good custom in virtues.\f*
\v 7 The richman ruleth over the poor: and he that borroweth is the servant of him that lendeth. \f + \fr 22:7 \ft Diligent travail.\f*
\v 8 He that soweth iniquity, shall reap evils, and with the rod of his wrath, he shall be consumed. \f + \fr 22:8 \ft Equity.\f*
\v 9 He that is prone to mercy shall be blessed: for of his breads he hath given to the poor. He that giveth gifts shall purchase victory and honour: but he that receiveth taketh away the soul of the giver. \f + \fr 22:9 \ft Alms deeds.\f* \f + \fr 22:9 \ft Better to give than to take.\f*
\v 10 Cast out the scorner, and brawling shall go forth with him, and cause shall cease and contumelies. \f + \fr 22:10 \ft Expel the incorrigible.\f*
\v 11 He that loveth cleanness of heart, for the grace of his lips, shall have the king his friend. \f + \fr 22:11 \ft Cleanness of heart.\f*
\v 12 The eyes of our Lord keep knowledge: and the words of the just are supplanted. \f + \fr 22:12 \ft The godly prosper.\f*
\v 13 The slothful saith: A lion is without, in the midst of the streets I am to be slain. \f + \fr 22:13 \ft Fortitude.\f*
\v 14 Adeep pit the mouth of a strange woman: he with whom our Lord is angry, shall fall into it. \f + \fr 22:14 \ft Care of chastity.\f*
\v 15 Folly is tied together in the heart of a child, and the rod of discipline shall drive it away. \f + \fr 22:15 \ft Chastisement.\f*
\v 16 He that doth calumniate the poor to increase his riches, himself shall give to a richer, and shall be in need. \f + \fr 22:16 \ft Compassion.\f*
\v 17 Incline thine ear, and hear the words of wisemen: and set thy heart to my doctrine: \f + \fr 22:17 \ft Rules of wisdom are necessary, profitable, and upon practice found pleasant: rightly directing all our thoughts, words and deeds.\f*
\v 18 which shall be beautiful for thee, when thou shalt keep it in thy belly, and it shall flow in thy lips.
\v 19 That thy confidence may be in our Lord, wherefore I have shewed also it to thee this day.
\v 20 Behold I have described it to thee three manner of ways: in cogitations and knowledge:
\v 21 that I might shew thee the stability, and the words of truth, out of these to answer them that sent thee.
\v 22 Do not violence to the poor, because he is poor: neither oppress the needy in the gate: \f + \fr 22:22 \ft Care of the poor; because they are dear to God.\f*
\v 23 because our Lord will judge his cause, and will pierce them, that have pierced his soul.
\v 24 Be not friend to an angry man, nor walk with a furious man: \f + \fr 22:24 \ft Fly from evil company which may corrupt thee.\f*
\v 25 lest perhaps thou learn his paths, and take scandal to thy soul.
\v 26 Be not with them that stick down their hands, and that offer themselves sureties for debts: \f + \fr 22:26 \ft Avoid suretyship, lest thou fall into distress.\f*
\v 27 for if thou have not wherewith to restore, what cause is there that he should take the covering from thy bed?
\v 28 Transgress not the ancient bounds, which thy fathers have put. \f + \fr 22:28 \ft Keep ancient traditions.\f*
\v 29 Hast thou seen a man quick in his work? He shall stand before kings, neither shall he be before the unnoble. \f + \fr 22:29 \ft Diligent travail.\f*
\c 23
\p
\v 1 When thou shalt sit to eat with a Prince, attend diligently what things are set before thy face: \f + \fr 23:1 \ft Modesty and discretion at the table of great persons.\f*
\v 2 and set a knife in thy throat, if notwithstanding thou have thy soul in thine own power. \f + \fr 23:2 \ft Mediocrity of riches, and contentment with mean state.\f*
\v 3 Desire not his meats, in which is the breath of lying.
\v 4 Labour not to be rich: but set a mean to thy prudence.
\v 5 Lift not up thine eyes to the riches, which thou canst not have: because they shall make to themselves wings as of an eagle, and shall fly into heaven.
\v 6 Eat not with an envious man, and desire not his meats. \f + \fr 23:6 \ft Eat not with a niggard, lest he be secretly grieved, outwardly dissembling, and thyself repent it.\f*
\v 7 Because after the similitude of a soothsayer, and diviner, he esteemeth that which he knoweth not. Eat and drink, will he say to thee: and his mind is not with thee.
\v 8 The meats which thou hadst eaten thou shalt vomit up: and shalt lose thy beautiful words.
\v 9 Speak not in the ears of the unwise: because they will despise the doctrine of thy speech. \f + \fr 23:9 \ft Advise not the uncapable.\f*
\v 10 Touch not the bounds of little ones: and into the field of pupils enter not. \f + \fr 23:10 \ft Hurt not orphans: for they are dear to God.\f*
\v 11 For their near kinsman is strong: and he will judge their cause against thee.
\v 12 Let thy heart enter into doctrine: and thine ears to words of knowledge. \f + \fr 23:12 \ft Diligent study of wisdom.\f*
\v 13 Withdraw not discipline from a child: for if thou shalt strike him with the rod, he shall not die. \f + \fr 23:13 \ft Moderate chastisement profiteth youth.\f*
\v 14 Thou shalt strike him with the rod: and deliver his soul from hell.
\v 15 My son, if thy mind shall be wise, my heart shall be glad with thee: \f + \fr 23:15 \ft Virtues of children are joyful to the parents.\f*
\v 16 And my reins shall rejoice, when thy lips shall speak right things.
\v 17 Let not thy heart envy sinners: but in the fear of our Lord be thou all the day: \f + \fr 23:17 \ft Contentment with God's will.\f*
\v 18 because thou shalt have hope in the later end, and thine exaltation shall not be taken away. \f + \fr 23:18 \ft Hope of reward.\f*
\v 19 Hear my son, & be wise: & direct thy mind in the way. \f + \fr 23:19 \ft Learn and practise wisdom.\f*
\v 20 Be not in the feasts of great drinkers, nor in their comessations, which contribute flesh together to eat:
\v 21 because they that are given to drinking, and that pay shots, shall be consumed, and drowsiness shall be clothed with rags. \f + \fr 23:21 \ft Sobriety and Temperance.\f*
\v 22 Hear thy father, that begot thee: and contemn not thy mother when she is old. \f + \fr 23:22 \ft Honour of parents.\f*
\v 23 Buy truth, and sell not wisdom, and doctrine, and intelligence. \f + \fr 23:23 \ft Wisdom most precious.\f*
\v 24 The father of the just rejoiceth with gladness: he that hath begotten a wiseman, shall rejoice in him. \f + \fr 23:24 \ft See. v. 15. and 16.\f*
\v 25 Let thy father be glad and thy mother, and let her rejoice that bare thee.
\v 26 My son give me thy heart: & let thine eyes keep my ways. \f + \fr 23:26 \ft Bodily and spiritual purity.\f*
\v 27 For an harlot is a deep ditch: & a strange woman a narrow pit.
\v 28 She lieth in wait in the way as a robber, and whom she shall see not circumspect, she will kill.
\v 29 To whom is woe? To whose father woe? To whom brawls? To whom ditches? To whom wounds without cause? To whom blood-shedding eyes? \f + \fr 23:29 \ft Detest drunkenness.\f*
\v 30 Is it not to them that pass their time in wine, and study to drink out their cups?
\v 31 Behold not wine when it waxeth yellow, when the colour thereof shall shine in the glass: it goeth in pleasantly, \f + \fr 23:31 \ft Drunkenness is deceitful,\f*
\v 32 but in the end, it will bite like a snake, and as a basilisk it will pour abroad poisons. \f + \fr 23:32 \ft dangerous,\f*
\v 33 Thine eyes shall see strange women, and thy heart shall speak perverse things. \f + \fr 23:33 \ft beastly,\f*
\v 34 And thou shalt be as one sleeping in the midst of the sea, and as the governor fast asleep, the stern being lost. \f + \fr 23:34 \ft hurtful to others,\f*
\v 35 And thou shalt say: They have beaten me, but I was not grieved: they drew me, and I felt not: When shall I awake, and find wines again? \f + \fr 23:35 \ft senseless, and unsatiable.\f*
\c 24
\p
\v 1 Emulate not evil men, neither desire thou to be with them: \f + \fr 24:1 \ft Fly evil company, lest thou be allured to vice.\f*
\v 2 because their mind doth meditate robberies, and their lips speak deceits.
\v 3 By wisdom the house shall be built, and by prudence it shall be strengthened. \f + \fr 24:3 \ft Wisdom and virtues, not wickedness, do prosper temporally and spiritually.\f*
\v 4 In doctrine the cellars shall be replenished with all precious and most beautiful substance.
\v 5 Awiseman is strong: and a learned man, strong and valiant.
\v 6 Because war is managed by due ordering: & there shall be salvation where many counsels are. \f + \fr 24:6 \ft Counsel in wars, and other great affairs.\f*
\v 7 Wisdom is high for a fool, in the gate he shall not open his mouth.
\v 8 He that thinketh to do evils, shall be called a fool. \f + \fr 24:8 \ft Good purposes.\f*
\v 9 The cogitation of a fool is sin: and a detracter the abomination of men. \f + \fr 24:9 \ft Report well of others.\f*
\v 10 If thou despair being weary in the day of distress: thy strength shall be diminished. \f + \fr 24:10 \ft Fortitude.\f*
\v 11 Deliver them that are led to death: and those that are drawn to death cease not to deliver. \f + \fr 24:11 \ft Works of mercy, according to our ability.\f*
\v 12 If thou say, I am not of force: he that seeth into the heart, he understandeth, and nothing deceiveth the keeper of thy soul, and he shall render to man according to his works.
\v 13 Eat honey my son, because it is good, and the honey-comb most sweet to thy throat: \f + \fr 24:13 \ft Wisdom is sweet:\f*
\v 14 so also the doctrine of wisdom to thy soul: which when thou shalt find, thou shalt have hope in the later end, and thy hope shall not perish. \f + \fr 24:14 \ft and giveth hope.\f*
\v 15 Lie not in wait, nor seek impiety in the house of the just, nor spoil his rest. \f + \fr 24:15 \ft Toleration of other's imperfections:\f*
\v 16 For seven times shall the just fall, and shall rise again: but the impious shall fall into evil. \f + \fr 24:16 \ft Oftentimes. S. Aug. li. 11. c. 31. civit.\f* \f + \fr 24:16 \ft Without which none liveth.\f*
\v 17 When thine enemy shall fall, be not glad, and in his ruin let not thy heart rejoice: \f + \fr 24:17 \ft Charity towards enemies.\f*
\v 18 Lest perhaps our Lord see, and it displease him, and he take away his wrath from him.
\v 19 Contend not with the most wicked, nor emulate the impious: \f + \fr 24:19 \ft Have peace with all, so much as may be.\f*
\v 20 because evil men have not hope of things to come, and the lamp of the impious shall be extinguished.
\v 21 Fear our Lord, my son, and the king: & with detracters meddle not: \f + \fr 24:21 \ft Loyalty to God & the King.\f*
\v 22 because their perdition shall suddenly rise; and the ruin of both who knoweth?
\v 23 These things also to the wise: to know a person in judgement is not good. \f + \fr 24:23 \ft Equity in judgement.\f*
\v 24 They that say to the impious: Thou art just; peoples shall curse them, and tribes shall detest them. \f + \fr 24:24 \ft Condemning the guilty, & delivering the innocent, is very grateful to all.\f*
\v 25 They that rebuke him, shall be praised: and blessing shall come upon them.
\v 26 He shall kiss the lips, who answereth right words.
\v 27 Prepare thy work abroad, and diligently till thy ground: that afterward thou mayst build thy house. \f + \fr 24:27 \ft Order in all affairs.\f*
\v 28 Be not witness without cause against thy neighbour: neither allure any man with thy lips. \f + \fr 24:28 \ft Discretion in bearing witness.\f*
\v 29 Say not, As he hath done to me, so will I do to him: I will render to every one according to his work. \f + \fr 24:29 \ft Revenge not.\f*
\v 30 I passed by the field of a slothful man, and by the vineyard of a foolish man: \f + \fr 24:30 \ft Diligent labour, and vigilance to provide necessaries, &\f*
\v 31 and behold nettles had filled it wholly, and thorns had covered the face thereof, and the wall of stones was destroyed.
\v 32 Which when I had seen, I laid it in my heart, and by the example I learned discipline.
\v 33 Alittle I say, thou shalt sleep, a little thou shalt slumber, a little shalt thou join thy hands together to rest:
\v 34 and as a post, poverty shall come to thee, & beggary as a man armed.
\c 25
\p
\v 1 These also are the parables of Salomon, which the men of Ezechias king of Juda wrote out. \f + \fr 25:1 \ft The 2. part. More Parables of Salomon written by others.\f*
\v 2 It is the glory of God to conceal the word, and the glory of kings to search the speech. \f + \fr 25:2 \ft God's works are not all revealed.\f*
\v 3 The heaven above, and the earth beneath, and the heart of kings is unscrutable. \f + \fr 25:3 \ft Kings have some secrets.\f*
\v 4 Take away the rust from silver, and there shall come forth a most pure vessel:
\v 5 Take away impiety from the king's countenance, and his throne shall be established with justice. \f + \fr 25:5 \ft Public justice and punishment of sin.\f*
\v 6 Appear not glorious before the king, and in the place of great men stand not. \f + \fr 25:6 \ft Modesty, and\f*
\v 7 For it is better that it be said to thee: Come up hither, than that thou be humbled before the Prince. \f + \fr 25:7 \ft Humility.\f*
\v 8 The things which thy eyes have seen, utter not quickly in a brawl: lest afterward thou canst not amend it, when thou hast dishonoured thy friend. \f + \fr 25:8 \ft Care of other's fame.\f*
\v 9 Treat thy cause with thy friend, and reveal not a secret to a stranger: \f + \fr 25:9 \ft Compose controversies secretly, rather than contend in public court.\f*
\v 10 lest perhaps he insult against thee when he heareth, and cease not to upbraid thee. Grace and friendship deliver : which keep to thyself, lest thou become reproachful. \f + \fr 25:10 \ft From fear.\f*
\v 11 Apples of gold in silver beds, he that speaketh a word in his time. \f + \fr 25:11 \ft Speak in due time.\f*
\v 12 Agolden earlet, and a shining precious stone, he that rebuketh a wiseman, and an obedient ear. \f + \fr 25:12 \ft Prudent admonition.\f*
\v 13 As the cold of snow in the day of harvest, so a faithful legate to him that sent him, maketh his soul to rest. \f + \fr 25:13 \ft Diligence in public affairs.\f*
\v 14 Clouds, and wind, and no rain following, a glorious man, and not accomplishing his promises. \f + \fr 25:14 \ft Performance of promised industry.\f*
\v 15 By patience the Prince shall be pacified, and a soft tongue shall break hardness. \f + \fr 25:15 \ft Meekness.\f*
\v 16 Thou hast found honey, eat that which sufficeth thee, lest perhaps being filled thou vomit it up. \f + \fr 25:16 \ft Temperance.\f*
\v 17 Withdraw thy foot from the house of thy neighbour, lest sometime having his fill he hate thee. \f + \fr 25:17 \ft Modesty.\f*
\v 18 Adart, and sword, and a sharp arrow, a man that speaketh false testimony against his neighbour. \f + \fr 25:18 \ft True testimony.\f*
\v 19 Arotten tooth, and weary foot, he that hopeth upon the unfaithful in the day of distress, \f + \fr 25:19 \ft Trust not a dissembler.\f*
\v 20 and that loseth his cloak in the day of cold. Vinegar in nitre, he that singeth songs to a naughty heart. As a moth the garment, and a worm the wood: so the sadness of a man hurteth the heart. \f + \fr 25:20 \ft * A consuming saltish hard earth.\f* \f + \fr 25:20 \ft Strive not with the incorrigible.\f* \f + \fr 25:20 \ft Alacrity.\f*
\v 21 If thine enemy shall hunger, give him meat: if he thirst, give him water to drink: \f + \fr 25:21 \ft Charity towards enemies.\f*
\v 22 for thou shalt heap hot coals upon his head, and our Lord will reward thee. \x + \xo 25:22 \xt Rom. 12.\x*
\v 23 The north-wind dissipateth rains, & a sad look the tongue that detracteth. \f + \fr 25:23 \ft Hear not detraction.\f*
\v 24 It is better to sit in a corner of the house top, than with a brawling woman, and in a common house. \f + \fr 25:24 \ft Domestical peace.\f*
\v 25 Cold water to a thirsty soul, and good tidings from a far country. \f + \fr 25:25 \ft Joy of well doing.\f*
\v 26 Afountain troubled with the foot, and a vein corrupted, the just falling before the impious. \f + \fr 25:26 \ft Profession of truth.\f*
\v 27 As he that eateth much honey, it is not good for him: so he that is a searcher of the majesty, shall be oppressed of the glory. \f + \fr 25:27 \ft Humility in knowledge.\f*
\v 28 As a city being open and without compass of walls, so a man that cannot repress his spirit in speaking. \f + \fr 25:28 \ft Government of the tongue.\f*
\c 26
\p
\v 1 As snow in the summer, and rain in the harvest: so is glory undecent for a fool. \f + \fr 26:1 \ft Advance not the vicious.\f*
\v 2 As a bird flying to other places, & a sparrow going whither he lift: so a curse uttered in vain shall light upon some man. \f + \fr 26:2 \ft Patience in false slander.\f*
\v 3 Awhip for a horse, and a snaffle for an ass, and a rod on the back of the unwise. \f + \fr 26:3 \ft Chastisement.\f*
\v 4 Answer not a fool according to his folly, lest thou be made like to him. \f + \fr 26:4 \ft Answer a fool wisely: detecting his folly.\f*
\v 5 Answer a fool according to his folly, lest he seem to himself to be wise.
\v 6 Lame of feet, and drinking iniquity, he that sendeth words by a foolish messenger. \f + \fr 26:6 \ft Place fit men in office:\f*
\v 7 As a lame man hath fair legs in vain: so a parable is undecent in the mouth of fools. \f + \fr 26:7 \ft Wise men in authority:\f*
\v 8 As he that casteth a stone into the heap of Mercury: so he that giveth honour to the unwise. \f + \fr 26:8 \ft Virtuous in honour, and\f*
\v 9 As if a thorn should grow in the hand of the drunkard: so a parable in the mouth of fools. \f + \fr 26:9 \ft Learned to teach.\f*
\v 10 Judgement determineth causes: and he that putteth a fool to silence, appeaseth angers. \f + \fr 26:10 \ft Make fools to keep silence.\f*
\v 11 As a dog that returneth to his vomit, so the unwise that reiterateth his folly. \f + \fr 26:11 \ft Return not to former sins.\f*
\v 12 Hast thou seen a man seem to himself wise? The fool shall have hope rather than he. \f + \fr 26:12 \ft Humble opinion of thyself.\f*
\v 13 The slothful saith: A lion is in the way, and a lioness in the journeys: \f + \fr 26:13 \ft Fortitude.\f*
\v 14 as a door turneth on his hinge so the slothful in his bed. \f + \fr 26:14 \ft Profitable labours.\f*
\v 15 The slothful hideth his hand under the arm-hole, and is grieved if he turneth it to his mouth. \f + \fr 26:15 \ft At least some good work.\f*
\v 16 The slothful seemeth wiser to himself, than seven men speaking sentences. \f + \fr 26:16 \ft Love not idleness.\f*
\v 17 As he that taketh a dog by the ears, so he that passeth by impatient, and meddleth with another man's brawl. \f + \fr 26:17 \ft Intermeddle not in brawls.\f*
\v 18 As he is hurtful that shooteth arrows and spears unto death:
\v 19 so a man that hurteth his friend fraudulently: and when he is taken withal saith: I did it in jest. \f + \fr 26:19 \ft Unfeigned friendship, especially in familiar acquaintance.\f*
\v 20 When wood faileth, the fire shall be extinguished: and the whisperer taken away, brawls cease. \f + \fr 26:20 \ft Punish bate-makers.\f*
\v 21 As coals to burning coals, and wood to fire, so an angry man raiseth brawls. \f + \fr 26:21 \ft Pacify the wrathful.\f*
\v 22 The words of the whisperer as it were simple, and the same come to the inmost parts of the belly. \f + \fr 26:22 \ft Hear not whisperers of evil reports.\f*
\v 23 As if thou wouldest adorn an earthen vessel with drossy silver, so swelling lips joined with a most wicked heart. \f + \fr 26:23 \ft Fly from hypocrites.\f*
\v 24 An enemy is perceived by his lips, when he shall handle deceits in his heart. \f + \fr 26:24 \ft Whose flattery and soft speech are suspicious, they will fall at last into their own traps, truth prevailing.\f*
\v 25 When he shall submit his voice, believe him not: because there are seven mischiefs in his heart.
\v 26 He that covereth hatred fraudulently, his malice shall be revealed in the councel.
\v 27 He that diggeth a pit, shall fall into it: and he that rolleth a stone, it shall return to him.
\v 28 Adeceitful tongue loveth not truth, and a slipper mouth worketh ruins.
\c 27
\p
\v 1 Boast not for tomorrow, being ignorant what the day to come may bring forth. \f + \fr 27:1 \ft Trust not to future uncertainties.\f*
\v 2 Let another praise thee, and not thine own mouth: a stranger and not thine own lips. \f + \fr 27:2 \ft Praise not thyself.\f*
\v 3 Astone is heavy, and sand weighty: but the anger of a fool is heavier than both. \f + \fr 27:3 \ft Beware of a fool's wrath:\f*
\v 4 Anger hath no mercy, nor fury breaking forth: and the violence of a moved spirit who can sustain? \f + \fr 27:4 \ft for it hath no mercy.\f*
\v 5 Better is manifest correption, than love hidden. \f + \fr 27:5 \ft Love friendly severity, not enemy's flattery.\f*
\v 6 Better are the wounds of him that loveth, than the fraudulent kisses of him that hateth.
\v 7 Asoul that is full shall tread upon the honeycomb: and a soul that is hungry shall take bitter also for sweet. \f + \fr 27:7 \ft Temperance in meat.\f*
\v 8 As a bird fleeting from her nest, so a man that forsaketh his place. \f + \fr 27:8 \ft Just care of thy family.\f*
\v 9 The heart is delighted with ointment and diverse odours: and with the good counsels of a friend the soul is sweetened. \f + \fr 27:9 \ft Esteem friendly counsel.\f*
\v 10 Thy friend, and thy father's friend do not leave: and go not into thy brother's house in the day of thine affliction. Better is a neighbour near than a brother far off. \f + \fr 27:10 \ft Old friends are better, & surer than a kinsman.\f*
\v 11 Study wisdom my son, & make my heart joyful, that thou mayst make answer to the upbraider. \f + \fr 27:11 \ft Be wise even for thy father's sake.\f*
\v 12 The subtle man seeing evil, hideth himself: little ones passing through have sustained evil detriments.
\v 13 Take his garment that hath been surety for a stranger: and for aliens take from him a pledge. \f + \fr 27:13 \ft Foresee and prevent dangers. Trust not enemies.\f*
\v 14 He that blesseth his neighbour with a loud voice, rising in the night, he shall be like him that curseth. \f + \fr 27:14 \ft Suspect extraordinary courtesy.\f*
\v 15 Roofs dropping through in the day of cold, and a brawling woman are compared together: \f + \fr 27:15 \ft Tolerate incorrigible brawlers with patience; lest they become worse by thy striving to amend them.\f*
\v 16 He that retaineth her, as he that should hold the wind, and shall call it the oil of his right hand.
\v 17 Iron is sharpened with iron, and a man sharpeneth the face of his friend.
\v 18 He that keepeth the figtree, shall eat the fruits thereof: and he that is the keeper of his master, shall be glorified. \f + \fr 27:18 \ft Conserve that is good.\f*
\v 19 As in waters the countenance of them that look therein shineth, so the hearts of men are manifest to the prudent. \f + \fr 27:19 \ft Conscience is best witness.\f*
\v 20 Hell and perdition are never filled: in like manner also the eyes of men are unsatiable. \f + \fr 27:20 \ft Contentment with our state.\f*
\v 21 As silver is tried in the forge, and gold in the furnace: so a man is proved by the mouth of him that praiseth. The heart of the wicked seeketh after evils, but the righteous heart seeketh after knowledge. \f + \fr 27:21 \ft Humility desireth not praise.\f* \f + \fr 27:21 \ft Right of heart.\f*
\v 22 If thou shall bray a fool in a mortar, as when a pestle striketh upon ptisane, his folly shall not be taken from him. \f + \fr 27:22 \ft Strive not to teach a fool.\f*
\v 23 Know diligently the countenance of thy cattle, and consider thy flocks: \f + \fr 27:23 \ft Discharge thy duty:\f*
\v 24 For thou shalt not have power always: but a crown shall be given into generation and generation. \f + \fr 27:24 \ft Whiles thou art in this life.\f*
\v 25 The meadows are open, and the green herbs have appeared, and the grass is gathered out of the mountains.
\v 26 Lambs for thy garment: and kids the price of the field.
\v 27 Let the milk of the goats suffice thee for thy meats, and for the necessities of thy house: and for victual to thy hand-maids. \f + \fr 27:27 \ft Be content with things necessary, and they shall be given to thee.\f* \x + \xo 27:27 \xt Matth. 6. v. 33.\x*
\c 28
\p
\v 1 The impious flyeth, no man pursuing: but the just confident as a lion, shall be without terror. \f + \fr 28:1 \ft Innocency is without fear.\f*
\v 2 For the sins of the land the Princes thereof shall be many: & for the wisdom of a man, & the knowledge of those things that are said, the life of the Prince shall be longer. \f + \fr 28:2 \ft General piety of the people procureth God's favour.\f*
\v 3 Apoor man calumniating the poor, is like a vehement shower, whereby famine is gotten. \f + \fr 28:3 \ft Neighbourly compassion.\f*
\v 4 They that forsake the law, praise the impious: they that keep it, are set on fire against him. \f + \fr 28:4 \ft Zeal of justice.\f*
\v 5 Evil men think not on judgment: but they that seek after our Lord, mark all things. \f + \fr 28:5 \ft Remember the day of judgement.\f*
\v 6 Better is a poor man walking in his simplicity, than the rich in crooked ways. \f + \fr 28:6 \ft Honesty and poverty.\f*
\v 7 He that keepeth the law is a wise son, but he that feedeth gluttons, shameth his father. \f + \fr 28:7 \ft Not want nor waste.\f*
\v 8 He that heapeth together riches by usuries and ocker, gathereth them for him that is liberal to the poor. \f + \fr 28:8 \ft Just gain in traffic.\f*
\v 9 He that turneth away his ears from hearing the law, his prayer shall be execrable. \f + \fr 28:9 \ft Obedience to magistrates.\f*
\v 10 He that deceiveth the just in a wicked way, shall fall into his destruction: and the simple shall possess his goods. \f + \fr 28:10 \ft Give counsel sincerely.\f*
\v 11 The rich man seemeth to himself wise: but the poor man being prudent shall search him. \f + \fr 28:11 \ft Humility in authority.\f*
\v 12 In the exultation of the just there is much glory: when the impious reign ruins of men. \f + \fr 28:12 \ft Place the godly in office.\f*
\v 13 He that hideth his wicked deeds, shall not be directed: but he that shall confess, and shall forsake them, shall obtain mercy. \f + \fr 28:13 \ft Acknowledge thy faults.\f*
\v 14 Blessed is the man that is always fearful: but he that is of an obstinate mind, shall fall into evil. \f + \fr 28:14 \ft Fear to offend.\f*
\v 15 Aroaring lion, and hungry bear, an impious Prince over the poor people. \f + \fr 28:15 \ft Clemency in Princes,\f*
\v 16 A Prince lacking prudence, shall oppress many by calumny: but he that hateth avarice, his days shall be made long. \f + \fr 28:16 \ft and prudent liberality.\f*
\v 17 Aman that doth calumniate the blood of a soul, if he shall fly into a lake, no man abideth. \f + \fr 28:17 \ft Revenge bloodshed.\f*
\v 18 He that walketh simply shall be saved: he that goeth perverse ways, shall fall once. \f + \fr 28:18 \ft Harmless life.\f*
\v 19 He that tilleth his ground, shall be filled with breads: but he that pursueth idleness, shall be replenished with poverty. \f + \fr 28:19 \ft Diligent labour.\f*
\v 20 Afaithful man shall be much praised: but he that hasteneth to be rich, shall not be innocent. \f + \fr 28:20 \ft Just dealing.\f*
\v 21 He that knoweth a person in judgement, doth not well: this man even for a morsel of bread forsaketh the truth. \f + \fr 28:21 \ft Just judgement.\f*
\v 22 Aman that hasteneth to be rich, and envieth others, is ignorant that poverty shall come upon him. \f + \fr 28:22 \ft Moderate gain.\f*
\v 23 He that rebuketh a man, shall afterward find favour with him, more than he that by flatteries of tongue deceiveth. \f + \fr 28:23 \ft Friendly correption.\f*
\v 24 He that pilfereth any thing from his father, and from his mother: & saith this is no sin, is the partaker of a mankiller. \f + \fr 28:24 \ft To rob parents is a grievous crime.\f*
\v 25 He that exalteth and dilateth himself, raiseth brawls: but he that trusteth in our Lord, shall be healed. \f + \fr 28:25 \ft Exalt not thyself.\f*
\v 26 He that hath confidence in his own heart, is a fool: but who so walketh wisely shall be saved. \f + \fr 28:26 \ft Trust not thine own judgement.\f*
\v 27 He that giveth to the poor, shall not lack: he that despiseth him that asketh shall sustain penury. \f + \fr 28:27 \ft Alms deeds.\f*
\v 28 When the impious shall rise, men shall be hid: when they shall perish, the just shall be multiplied. \f + \fr 28:28 \ft Godly magistrates.\f*
\c 29
\p
\v 1 The man that with stiff neck contemneth him that rebuketh, sudden destruction shall come upon him: and health shall not follow him. \f + \fr 29:1 \ft Love to be corrected.\f*
\v 2 In the multiplication of just men, the common people shall rejoice: when the impious shall take princedom, the people shall mourn. \f + \fr 29:2 \ft Choose godly magistrates.\f*
\v 3 Aman that loveth wisdom, maketh his father glad: but he that maintaineth harlots, shall destroy his substance. \f + \fr 29:3 \ft Love wisdom.\f*
\v 4 Ajust king setteth up the land, a covetous man shall destroy it. \f + \fr 29:4 \ft Just and liberal magistrates.\f*
\v 5 Aman that with fair and feigned words speaketh to his friend, spreadeth a net to his steps. \f + \fr 29:5 \ft Sincere amity.\f*
\v 6 Asnare shall entangle the wicked man sinning: and the just shall praise and rejoice. \f + \fr 29:6 \ft Just joy of the wicked's fall.\f*
\v 7 The just knoweth the cause of the poor: the impious is ignorant of knowledge. \f + \fr 29:7 \ft Compassion of the poor.\f*
\v 8 Pestilent men dissipate a city: but the wise turn away fury. \f + \fr 29:8 \ft Care of common good.\f*
\v 9 Awise man, if he contend with a fool, whether he be angry, or whether he laugh, shall not find rest. \f + \fr 29:9 \ft Contend not with a fool.\f*
\v 10 Men of blood hate the simple: but just men seek his soul. \f + \fr 29:10 \ft Defend the just.\f*
\v 11 Afool uttereth all his spirit: a wiseman deferreth and reserveth till afterward. \f + \fr 29:11 \ft Discretion in just anger.\f*
\v 12 A Prince that gladly heareth words of lying, hath all his servants impious. \f + \fr 29:12 \ft Detestation of lying.\f*
\v 13 The poor man and the creditor have met one another: our Lord is illuminator of both. \f + \fr 29:13 \ft Contentment in state of life.\f*
\v 14 The king that judgeth the poor in truth, his throne shall be replenished for ever. \f + \fr 29:14 \ft Equity in judgement.\f*
\v 15 Rod and rebuke giveth wisdom: but the child that is left to his own will, confoundeth his mother. \f + \fr 29:15 \ft Chastisement of youth.\f*
\v 16 In the multiplication of the impious, wickedness shall be multiplied, and the just shall see the ruins of them. \f + \fr 29:16 \ft God never permitteth all to be evil.\f*
\v 17 Nurture thy son, and he shall refresh thee, and shall give delights to thy soul. \f + \fr 29:17 \ft Instruct children.\f*
\v 18 When prophecy shall fail, the people shall be dissipated: but he that keepeth the Law, is blessed. \f + \fr 29:18 \ft Pray to have good Pastors.\f*
\v 19 Aservant cannot be taught by words: because he understandeth that which thou sayst, and contemneth to answer. \f + \fr 29:19 \ft Compel the froward to obey.\f*
\v 20 Hast thou seen a man swift to speak? Folly is rather to be hoped, than his amendment. \f + \fr 29:20 \ft Consideration in speaking.\f*
\v 21 He that nourished his servant delicately from his childhood, afterward shall feel him stubborn. \f + \fr 29:21 \ft Subdue the flesh to the spirit.\f*
\v 22 An angry man provoketh brawls: and he that is easy to indignation, shall be more prone to sin. \f + \fr 29:22 \ft Meekness.\f*
\v 23 Humiliation followeth the proud: and glory shall receive the humble of spirit. \f + \fr 29:23 \ft Humility.\f*
\v 24 He that is partaker with a thief, hateth his own soul: he heareth one adjuring, and telleth not. \f + \fr 29:24 \ft Participate not with sin.\f*
\v 25 He that feareth man, shall soon fall: he that trusteth in our Lord shall be lifted up. \f + \fr 29:25 \ft Fear not men in God's cause,\f*
\v 26 Many seek after the face of the Prince: & the judgement of every one cometh forth from our Lord. \f + \fr 29:26 \ft remembering that God is Judge of all.\f*
\v 27 The just abhor an impious man: & the impious abhor them that are in the right way. The son that keepeth the word, shall be out of perdition. \f + \fr 29:27 \ft Hate all wickedness.\f* \f + \fr 29:27 \ft Obey spiritual and temporal parents.\f*
\c 30
\p
\v 1 The words of the Gatherer the son of Vomiter. The vision, that the man spake, with whom God is, and who being strengthened by God abiding with him, said:
\v 2 I am most foolish of men, & the wisdom of men is not with me. \f + \fr 30:2 \ft The wisest man best knoweth that he wanteth much of perfect wisdom yet in his humility supposeth, that others have attained somewhat more than himself.\f*
\v 3 I have not learned wisdom, and have not known the science of saints.
\v 4 Who hath ascended into heaven and descended? Who hath contained the spirit in his hands? Who hath bound the waters together as in a garment? Who hath raised up all the borders of the earth? What is his name, and what is the name of his son, if thou know? \f + \fr 30:4 \ft Christ the Son of God is wisdom itself and as the Son of man hath perfect wisdom.\f*
\v 5 Every word of God tried by fire, is a buckler to them that hope in him:
\v 6 Add not any thing to his words, and so thou be reproved and found a liar.
\v 7 Two things I have asked thee, deny them not to me before I die.
\v 8 Vanity, and lying words make far from me. Beggary, and riches give me not: give only things necessary for my sustenance:
\v 9 lest perhaps being filled I be allured to deny, and may say: Who is the Lord? Or being compelled by poverty I may steal, and forswear the name of my God.
\v 10 Accuse not a servant to his master, lest perhaps he curse thee, and thou fall. \f + \fr 30:10 \ft Bondslaves are to be pitied, and not affliction added to the afflicted.\f*
\v 11 There is a generation that curseth their father, and that blesseth not their mother. \f + \fr 30:11 \ft Four execrable vices: Ingratitude, Hypocrisy. Insolency: Oppression of the poor.\f*
\v 12 Ageneration, that seemeth to it-self clean, & yet is not washed from their filthiness.
\v 13 Ageneration, whose eyes are lofty, and the eye-lids thereof set up on high.
\v 14 Ageneration, that for teeth hath swords, and chaweth with their grinding teeth, that they may eat the needy out of the earth, and the poor from among men.
\v 15 The horseleech hath two daughters that say: Bring, bring. Three things are unsatiable, the fourth never saith it sufficeth. \f + \fr 30:15 \ft things are unsatiable, the fourth never saith it sufficeth.\f*
\v 16 Hell, and the mouth of the matrice, & the earth which is not satisfied with water: but the fire never saith it sufficeth.
\v 17 The eye that scorneth his father, & that despiseth the travail of his mother in bearing him, let the ravens of the torrents pick it out, and the young of the eagle eat it. \f + \fr 30:17 \ft Dishonour of parents shall be severely punished.\f*
\v 18 Three things are hard to me, and of the fourth I am utterly ignorant.
\v 19 The way of an eagle in the air, the way of a serpent upon a rock, the way of a ship in the midst of the sea, and the way of a man in youth. \f + \fr 30:19 \ft Young men following carnal appetite, can no more give account of their actions, than of the ways which an eagle, a serpent and a ship have passed.\f*
\v 20 Such is also the way of an adulterous woman, which eateth, and wiping her mouth saith: I have done no evil.
\v 21 By three things the earth is moved, and the fourth it cannot sustain.
\v 22 By a servant when he shall reign: by a fool when he shall be filled with meat:
\v 23 by an odious woman when she shall be taken in matrimony: & by a bond-woman when she shall be heir to her mistress.
\v 24 There are four the least things of the earth, and they are wiser than the wise. \f + \fr 30:24 \ft By these examples are commended four virtues, Industry, Prudence, Concord, and Humility.\f*
\v 25 The ants, a weak people, which prepareth in the harvest meat for themselves:
\v 26 The leveret, a people not strong, which placeth his bed in the rock:
\v 27 The locust hath no king, and they go out all by their troops:
\v 28 The stellion stayeth on his hands, & tarrieth in king's houses.
\v 29 There are three things which go well, and the fourth that goeth happily. \f + \fr 30:29 \ft Other four Fortitude, Chastity, Order, and Justice.\f*
\v 30 The lion, the strongest of beasts shall fear at the meeting of none:
\v 31 the cock girded about the loins, and the ram: also the king, against whom none can resist.
\v 32 There is that hath appeared a fool after that he was lifted up on high: for if he had understood, he would have laid his hand upon his mouth. \f + \fr 30:32 \ft Fools ought not to govern.\f*
\v 33 And he that strongly presseth the paps to wring out milk, straineth out butter, and he that violently cleanseth his nose, wringeth out blood: & he that provoketh angers, bringeth forth discords. \f + \fr 30:33 \ft Moderation is necessary in all actions.\f*
\c 31
\p
\v 1 The words of Lamuel the king. The vision wherewith his mother instructed him. \f + \fr 31:1 \ft Words pertaining to Salomon, spoken to him by his mother: who here calleth him Lamuel, signifying, God with him.\f*
\v 2 What o my beloved, what o the beloved of my womb, what o beloved of my vows?
\v 3 Give not thy substance to women, & thy riches to destroy kings.
\v 4 Give not to kings, o Lamuel, give not wine to kings: because there is no secret where drunkenness reigneth,
\v 5 & lest perhaps they drink, & forget judgments, & change the cause of the children of the poor.
\v 6 Give strong drink to them that be sad, and wine unto them that are of a pensive mind:
\v 7 let them drink, and forget their poverty, and not remember their sorrow any more.
\v 8 Open thy mouth to the dumb, & to the causes of all the children that pass: \f + \fr 31:8 \ft Doctrine is most profitable to those, that are modestly dumb, more willing to hear than to speak.\f*
\v 9 open thy mouth, decree that which is just, & judge the needy & poor. \f + \fr 31:9 \ft The chief & most proper office of a King is to do justice.\f*
\v 10 Avaliant woman who shall find? Far, and from the utmost borders is the price of her. \f + \fr 31:10 \ft Awoman of such perfection as is here described, is indeed rare, yet possible to be found.\f*
\v 11 The heart of her husband trusteth in her, and he shall not need spoils.
\v 12 She shall render good, and not evil, all the days of her life.
\v 13 She hath sought wool and flax, and hath wrought by the counsel of her hands.
\v 14 She is become as a merchant's ship, bringing her bread from far.
\v 15 And she hath risen in the night, and given prey to her household, and meats to her handmaids.
\v 16 She hath viewed a field, and bought it, of the fruit of her hands she hath planted a vineyard.
\v 17 She hath girded her loins with strength, and hath strengthened her arm.
\v 18 She hath tasted, and seen that her traffic is good: her lamp shall not be extinguished in the night.
\v 19 She hath put her hand to strong things, and her fingers have taken hold of the spindle. \f + \fr 31:19 \ft Flax on the distaff signifieth purpose to do good works, yarn on the spindle the work well begun, which giveth confidence in God that the same shall be perfect and have due reward.\f*
\v 20 She hath opened her hand to the needy, and stretched out her palms to the poor.
\v 21 She shall not fear for her house in the colds of snow: for all her household are clothed with double.
\v 22 Tapestry clothing she hath made to herself: silk and purple is her garment.
\v 23 Her husband is noble in the gates, when he shall sit with the senators of the land.
\v 24 She made sindon, and sold it, and delivered a girdle to the Chananeite. \f + \fr 31:24 \ft They make and sell cloth, which learning and observing God's law, do teach it others.\f*
\v 25 Strength and beauty is her garment, and she shall laugh in the later day.
\v 26 She hath opened her mouth to wisdom, and the law of clemency is in her tongue.
\v 27 She hath considered the paths of her house, and hath not eaten her bread idle.
\v 28 Her children arose, and commended her to be most blessed: her husband, and he praised her.
\v 29 Many daughters have gathered together riches: thou hast passed them all.
\v 30 Grace is deceitful, and beauty is vain: the woman that feareth our Lord shall be praised. \f + \fr 31:30 \ft External comeliness is not durable: but the fear of God is more worthy of praise.\f*
\v 31 Give ye to her of the fruit of her hands, and let her works praise her in the gates. \f + \fr 31:31 \ft Good works shall be rewarded,\f* \f + \fr 31:31 \ft at the tribunal seat of judgement.\f*
